"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458882","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-14","<p>Schedule 1 of the Freedom of Information Act sets out that the BBC is subject to that act, in respect of information held for purposes other than those of journalism, art or literature. The BBC's website sets out how general exemptions to the Freedom of Information Act may apply to Freedom of Information requests to the BBC. You can find it here (http://www.bbc.co.uk/foi/).</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-14T15:42:09.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458882/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458882/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458882/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-09","BBC: Royal Charters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 8 March 2016 to Question 29543, which areas of the BBC are exempt from the Freedom of Information Act 2000.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","30400"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458883","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","true","2016-03-14","<p>The BBC Charter Review Consultation Paper, published in July 2015, set out the issues for consideration in Charter Review. The Government will set out its proposals in a White Paper in Spring.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><del class="ministerial">The Government is taking forward a range of measures to tackle nuisance calls, which will increase consumer protection and choice by strengthening the Information Commissioner's Office's (ICO) ability to take enforcement action against organisations that break the law. Specific actions include consulting on making it a requirement for direct marketing callers to display calling line identification; strengthening the ICO's direct marketing guidance; and exploring extending the ICO’s powers of compulsory audit to more of the organisations that generate nuisance calls. Baroness Neville-Rolfe's speech on the subject to the Direct Marketing Authority can be found at:<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/baroness-nevile-rolfe-on-data-protection-and-nuisance-calls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/baroness-nevile-rolfe-on-data-protection-and-nuisance-calls</a></del></p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-14T15:44:38.067Z","2016-03-15T16:23:13.733Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458883/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458883/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458883/answer","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458883/answer/previousversion/51104","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-09","BBC: Royal Charters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, which areas of the BBC Charter he will seek to reform in upcoming negotiations with the BBC Trust.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","30401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458884","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-14","<p>The BBC Charter Review Consultation Paper, published in July 2015, set out the issues for consideration in Charter Review, including Freedom of Information. The Government will set out its proposals in a White Paper in Spring.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-14T15:43:10.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458884/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458884/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458884/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-09","BBC: Royal Charters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 8 March 2016 to Question 29543, what steps he plans to take to reform the BBC's exposure to the Freedom of Information Act 2000 as part of the Charter Review.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","30402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458885","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-14","<p>Defence records show there have been no civilian casualities as a result of UK military action in any operational theatre in the last 12 months.</p><p>We take very seriously our responsibility to protect innocent civilian life when planning UK military operations. Our targeting procedures are rigorous, and we take every possible precaution to ensure that no civilian lives are lost when conducting strike missions.</p><p>If we had any reason to believe - either from our own analysis or from other reports - that there might have been civilian casualties, a full investigation would be conducted.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-03-14T16:04:26.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458885/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458885/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458885/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-09","Military Intervention: Casualties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many civilian casualties have resulted from direct UK military action in each theatre of operation in each of the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","30452"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458886","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-14","<p>No civilians rescued from the Mediterranean Sea by the Royal Navy in the last two years were medically evacuated. Where Royal Navy vessels rescued migrants, medical treatment was administered on board if required. All those rescued were disembarked at agreed ports of safety in Italy.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-03-14T16:03:41.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458886/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458886/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458886/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-09","Rescue Services: Mediterranean Sea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many civilians rescued from the Mediterranean Sea by the Royal Navy in the last two years requested medical evacuation; and to what locations such people were transported for treatment.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","30453"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458887","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-16","<p>In the context of defence-related sites, 'strategic asset status' is not a recognised term.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-03-16T16:13:43.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458887/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458887/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458887/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-09","Rosyth Dockyard","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department has assessed the potential merits of giving the Rosyth Dockyard strategic asset status.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","30509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458888","Department for Education","false","2016-03-15","<p>The Government greatly values the long-standing contribution that existing church and faith schools play in our education system and have no plans to extend the 50% limit to these schools as they are already providing high quality places in their local areas.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-03-15T13:36:48.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458888/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458888/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458888/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-09","Faith Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the potential benefits of extending the 50 per cent cap on religious selection in free schools to all state-funded schools in England.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","30443"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458889","Department for Education","false","2016-03-15","<p>Faith schools form an important part of our diverse education system and provide places for the children of parents who wish their children to be educated within a religious context.</p><p> </p><p>Local authorities (LAs) are responsible for providing sufficient school places, as set out under section 14(1) of the 1996 Education Act. LAs organise their place planning on the basis of circumstances specific to their authority. LAs that have faith schools are expected to take into account any impact on local place planning as part of their strategy to provide sufficient school places.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-03-15T17:21:55.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458889/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458889/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458889/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-09","Faith Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent assessment she has made of the effect of religious selection on the availability of school places and the number of parents who are unable to get their children into their local school.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","30444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458890","Department for Education","false","2016-03-14","<p>The Schools Adjudicator reports annually to the Secretary of State on school admissions. Her most recent report, published on 17 December 2015, takes account of the impact school admission arrangements may have on parents’ ability to navigate the admissions process. We are giving careful consideration to the findings of this report in our current review of the School Admissions Code and will conduct a full public consultation in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The report can be found here: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/osa-annual-report" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/osa-annual-report</a></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-03-14T15:21:36.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458890/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458890/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458890/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-09","Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of (a) divergences between schools' admission arrangements and (b) the effect of such divergence on parents' ability to navigate the admissions process.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","30468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458891","Department for Education","false","2016-03-14","<p>It is the role of the Schools Adjudicator to determine whether school admission arrangements comply with the Schools Admissions Code.</p><p>The Regional Schools Commissioners (RSCs) are responsible for approving new academies and intervening in underperforming academies and maintained schools in their area. The RSCs also have a limited role in agreeing admissions changes in open academies.</p><p>The specific range of circumstances where an RSC would take decisions on admissions arrangements in open academies is as follows:</p><ul><li><p>Where the Trust of an academy, free school, University Technical College (UTC) or studio school has requested a variation of its admissions arrangements outside the normal timeframe for consulting on and determining admissions.</p></li><li><p>Where, following a code-complaint consultation by the Trust, the academy requests a change to any admissions arrangements that are written into the funding agreement.</p></li><li><p>Where an academy, free school, UTC or studio school has requested a post-opening ‘derogation’ from the requirement to comply with the code, but only where there is an existing policy precedent.</p></li></ul>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-03-14T14:53:32.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458891/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458891/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458891/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-09","Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 29 February 2016 to Question 27310, if she will extend the remit of regional school commissioners to include an active role in monitoring the compliance of schools' admission policies with the School Admissions Code.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","30471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458892","Department for Education","false","2016-03-14","<p>Admission authorities for schools with a religious character already have the discretion to prioritise all looked after and previously looked after children in their oversubscription criteria, regardless of their faith, and many schools do so.</p><p> </p><p>The Chief Schools Adjudicator reports annually to the Secretary of State on fair access. We are giving careful consideration to the findings of her report for 2014–2015 as part of our current review of the School Admissions Code. We will be conducting a full public consultation in due course.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-03-14T15:19:47.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458892/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458892/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458892/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-09","Faith Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 29 February 2016 to Question 27309, if she will make an assessment of the potential merits of requiring religiously selective schools to prioritise looked-after and previously looked-after children without reference to religion in the upcoming consultation on the School Admissions Code.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","30415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458893","Department for Education","false","2016-03-15","<p>A list of the summer school allocations for 2015-16 is available on GOV.UK at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pupil-premium-summer-schools-programme-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pupil-premium-summer-schools-programme-2014</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The list includes the names of all secondary schools who received summer school grant funding in 2015-16.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-03-15T17:18:04.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458893/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458893/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458893/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-09","Pupils: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 4 February 2016 to Question 24532, which secondary schools took part in the 2015 summer school programme.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","30406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458894","Department for Education","false","2016-03-15","<p>A decision to end the summer schools programme was made as part of the Spending Review in autumn 2015, and the ending of this specific grant in 2016/17 was included in revenue funding information published on 17 December 2015 in the Education Funding Agency bulletin to schools, colleges, local authorities and other 16 to 19 providers. A copy of this bulletin is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/efa-e-bulletin-17-december-2015-issue-112" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/efa-e-bulletin-17-december-2015-issue-112</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Schools can continue to run a summer school if they wish to, and they will be able to use their pupil premium allocation to fund places for their disadvantaged pupils. Schools are held to account for the progress and attainment of their disadvantaged pupils through performance tables and Ofsted inspection. The Department does not monitor how individual schools spend the pupil premium.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","30408","2016-03-15T17:14:50.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458894/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458894/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458894/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-09","Pupil Premium: Summer Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 4 February 2016 to Question 24532, how much funding from the pupil premium her Department plans to make available to support schools in delivering summer school programmes in 2016.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","30407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458895","Department for Education","false","2016-03-15","<p>A decision to end the summer schools programme was made as part of the Spending Review in autumn 2015, and the ending of this specific grant in 2016/17 was included in revenue funding information published on 17 December 2015 in the Education Funding Agency bulletin to schools, colleges, local authorities and other 16 to 19 providers. A copy of this bulletin is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/efa-e-bulletin-17-december-2015-issue-112" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/efa-e-bulletin-17-december-2015-issue-112</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Schools can continue to run a summer school if they wish to, and they will be able to use their pupil premium allocation to fund places for their disadvantaged pupils. Schools are held to account for the progress and attainment of their disadvantaged pupils through performance tables and Ofsted inspection. The Department does not monitor how individual schools spend the pupil premium.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","30407","2016-03-15T17:14:50.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458895/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458895/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458895/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-09","Pupils: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 4 February 2016 to Question 24532, on pupils: disadvantaged, how many of the 2,171 secondary schools that chose to take part in the 2015 summer schools programme have confirmed that they will be taking part in 2016.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","30408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458896","Department for Education","false","2016-03-14","<p>The Standards and Testing Agency (STA) provides detailed statutory guidance for schools and teachers to follow in the administration of Key Stage 1 and Key Stage 2 tests. The guidance on test administration is specifically in Section 6 of the Assessment Reporting Arrangements (ARAs) which can be found here:</p><ul><li><p>For Key Stage 1 - <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/2016-key-stage-1-assessment-and-reporting-arrangements-ara" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/2016-key-stage-1-assessment-and-reporting-arrangements-ara</a></p></li><li><p>For Key Stage 2 - <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/2016-key-stage-2-assessment-and-reporting-arrangements-ara" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/2016-key-stage-2-assessment-and-reporting-arrangements-ara</a></p></li></ul><p> </p><p>The STA published sample questions in summer 2014 in addition to complete sample tests in summer 2015 to give primary schools nearly a year of lead-in time to prepare for the new tests.</p><p>A clarification document was published on 8 March 2016 to address any misunderstandings that there may have been with the guidance regarding statutory teacher assessment. This document can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/clarification-key-stage-1-and-2-teacher-assessment-and-moderation-guidance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/clarification-key-stage-1-and-2-teacher-assessment-and-moderation-guidance</a></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-03-14T15:24:35.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458896/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458896/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458896/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-09","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what support her Department is giving to teachers to assist them with the new Key Stage 1 and Key Stage 2 tests.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","30449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458897","Department for Education","false","2016-03-14","<p>The Careers &amp; Enterprise Company (CEC) is a key part of our strategy to transform the provision of careers, enterprise and employer engagement for young people to inspire them and prepare them for the world of work.</p><p> </p><p>We are funding the CEC to roll out and manage its Enterprise Adviser Network, which was launched in September 2015. Recruitment is ongoing and there are currently 58 Enterprise Coordinators working in 32 Local Enterprise Partnerships (LEPs), with 173 Enterprise Advisers working directly with schools and colleges to support their careers and enterprise provision. LEPs are prioritising schools and colleges using local knowledge and available data, including destinations data, level of employer engagement and apprenticeships take-up. The CEC is responsible for the administrative resources provided to the network.</p><p> </p><p>In January, my Rt Hon Friend the Prime Minister announced an investment of £70 million in our careers strategy over this Parliament and confirmed that there will be continued funding for the CEC to build on the excellent work it has begun, embedding and further extending its projects already underway, including the Enterprise Adviser Network. We have not yet finalised how much will be spent each year or how it will be allocated.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","30446 ; 30447","2016-03-14T17:46:27.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458897/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458897/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458897/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-09","Enterprise Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many enterprise advisers her Department has appointed to work with (a) schools and (b) further edcuation colleges in England.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","30445"
