"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458935","Department for International Development","false","2016-03-16","<p>DFID’s Disability Framework, published in 2015, recognises that including people with disabilities through local Disabled Person’s Organisations (DPOs) in the design, delivery and monitoring and evaluation of policy and programmes is critically important. This means both hearing first-hand the challenges people with disabilities are facing and identifying effective approaches for collectively addressing these challenges.</p><p>Many DFID country offices are engaging directly with local people with disabilities to shape and direct their work. For example, in Rwanda we are engaged with the National Council of Disabled Persons and the National Union of Disabled Organisations of Rwanda (NUDOR), which represents a large number of DPOs. Through our partnerships with VSO, Disability Rights Fund (DRF), Manusher Jonno Foundation, and ADD International we are funding more than 100 DPOs in more than 20 countries to push for human rights and to improve lives for people with disabilities.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-03-16T15:55:48.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458935/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458935/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458935/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-03-09","Developing Countries: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how her Department plans to increase its engagement with people with disabilities and representative organisations in its priority countries.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","30430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458936","Department for International Development","false","2016-03-16","<p>DFID follows a ‘twin-track’ approach to disability inclusion. This means we aim to attach priority to disability in all our policies and programmes as well as supporting disability-targeted programmes. Last year we conducted a review of our first year of implementing the Disability Framework. This involved working closely with civil society partners and our stakeholders to invite their assessment of our progress and to analyse the information we received, assessing staff capability on disability inclusion and gathering feedback from DFID country offices and central teams on how they had delivered on Framework commitments.</p><p>We will consider conducting a similar approach moving forward.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-03-16T15:55:07.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458936/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458936/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458936/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-03-09","Developing Countries: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how her Department plans to review work under the Disability Framework and report its outcomes in 2018.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","30431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458937","Department for International Development","false","2016-03-16","<p>DFID follows a ‘twin-track’ approach to disability inclusion. This means we attach priority to disability in all our policies and programmes as well as supporting disability-targeted programmes.</p><p>We have made significant progress in mainstreaming disability inclusion in our humanitarian response, including the development of an internal guidance note on ageing and disability in humanitarian response. We will build on this foundation by supporting partners to deliver on our commitment to include disaggregated data on age and disability as part of our requirements for funding humanitarian proposals, and advocating for the use of the Minimum Standards on Ageing and Disability Inclusion with humanitarian partners to improve the mainstreaming of the principles of inclusion.</p><p>DFID has funded the Disability Rights Fund (DRF) since its inception in 2008 and our current grant of over £2.6 million between 2013 and 2016 reinforces our commitment to the DRF. With support from DFID, the DRF supports Disabled People’s Organisations in the developing world to take the lead in advocating for the human rights of people with disabilities at local and national levels.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-03-16T15:56:28.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458937/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458937/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458937/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-03-09","Developing Countries: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how her Department plans to implement its Disability Framework.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","30432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458938","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-14","<p>The Government’s sympathies are with the victims and friends and families of those who lost their lives and were injured in this terrible attack.</p><p> </p><p>Decisions on funding individual cases are taken independently by the Legal Aid Agency. The decision not to provide legal aid funding for this claim for damages was made as it does not meet the criteria set by Parliament. Ministers are prevented by law from intervening in the individual decisions of the Legal Aid Agency.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-03-14T16:44:42.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458938/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458938/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458938/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-09","Terrorism: Hyde Park","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will conduct an urgent review of the Legal Aid Agency's decision to refuse a request to fund a civil case into the Hyde Park bombing.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","30414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458939","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-17","<p>The proportion of 16 to 17 year old offenders who were found to have been convicted of committing a second knife offence and received the mandatory four months Detention and Training Order during the period 17 July to 31 December 2015 is available here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/knife-possession-sentencing-quarterly-brief-october-to-december-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/knife-possession-sentencing-quarterly-brief-october-to-december-2015</a></p><p>Any decisions and assessments taken regarding the minimum mandatory penalty are made solely by the courts. Whilst the 4 month DTO is the minimum custodial term available for 16 to 17 year old offenders, the courts also have the power to set aside the minimum term in the event of a guilty plea and/or if time has been served in custody on remand or on a tag. A decision by the courts to reduce the minimum term will result in a community penalty.</p><p>The published figures will change when the outcomes of cases passing through the criminal justice system become available on the Police National Computer. On average it takes 86 days from charging an offender for a knife possession offence to the offender receiving the court outcome. Data for the next quarter is due to be published on 9 June 2016.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-03-17T17:46:43.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458939/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458939/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458939/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-09","Young Offenders: Knives","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, in (a) how many and (b) what proportion of cases of 16 and 17 year olds being convicted of committing a second knife offence the perpetrator received the mandatory four months Detention and Training Order during the quarter ending 31 December 2015.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","30392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458940","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-16","<p>The MedCo IT portal became operational in April 2015, its purpose being to enhance the independence and standards of medical reporting in respect of whiplash claims.</p><p>As of 14 March 2016, 503,000 searches resulting in the selection of a Medical Reporting Organisation or an individual medical expert have been made on the MedCo system. These searches have been by authorised users of the system, usually solicitors acting for prospective claimants in whiplash cases. Management information related to these searches is regularly scrutinised by MedCo to identify potential issues.</p><p>The impact of the new MedCo system is currently under review and a report detailing the outcomes of this review will be published by the Ministry of Justice in due course.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-03-16T12:06:16.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458940/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458940/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458940/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-09","Personal Injury","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the MedCo Portal in tracking whiplash claims.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","30505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458941","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-17","<p>The Local Sustainable Transport Fund supported 44 projects in 2015/16. The Sustainable Travel Transition Year competition is currently live so we cannot confirm how many projects it will support. The Access Fund has not yet been launched and we are therefore unable to estimate the number of bids it might support.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-17T13:40:10.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458941/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458941/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458941/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-09","Transport: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 25 February 2016 to Question 26735, how many schemes he expects to be funded (a) by the Local Sustainable Transport Fund in 2015-16, (b) during the Sustainable Travel Transition Year in 2016-17 and (c) by the Access Fund in 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","30398"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458942","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-17","<p>At a local level, the provision of cycling infrastructure is for local authorities to decide. The funding is there for any local area to invest in cycling if they wish to.</p><p> </p><p>At the Spending Review, the Government reaffirmed its commitment to walking and cycling. This included a new Access fund for sustainable travel and our Road Investment Strategy for 2015-20, which includes plans to improve 200 sections of the road network in England for cyclists. In addition, there is now long-term funding available for cycling from the Integrated Transport Block, Highways Maintenance block, and the Local Growth Fund.</p><p> </p><p>We have also launched the Sustainable Travel Transition Year, which is a £20m revenue competition; boosting cycling and walking levels is one of the strategic objectives of this fund. Funding will be awarded competitively, and we will not apply a regional bias.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-17T13:45:11.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458942/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458942/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458942/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-09","Cycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 2 February 2016 to Question 24092, what steps his Department is taking to tackle regional differences in cycling funding across England and for the (a) East Midlands, (b) North East and (c) East of England.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","30399"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458943","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-17","<p>In June 2014 the Department for Transport commissioned a comprehensive three-year research project into the effects of 20mph limits.</p><p> </p><p>Effects to be assessed include the impacts of 20mph limit schemes on collision and casualty levels, changes in traffic flow and impacts on air quality and noise.</p><p> </p><p>Evidence is being taken from twelve core case study schemes which cover a variety of area types from metropolitan and city centre locations to small town and residential areas. Three further case studies cover local authorities that have chosen not to implement 20mph schemes.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","30404 ; 30405","2016-03-17T15:46:50.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458943/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458943/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458943/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-09","Speed Limits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will assess the effect of the introduction of 20 miles per hour speed limits in residential areas on the number of accidents.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","30403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458944","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-17","<p>In June 2014 the Department for Transport commissioned a comprehensive three-year research project into the effects of 20mph limits.</p><p> </p><p>Effects to be assessed include the impacts of 20mph limit schemes on collision and casualty levels, changes in traffic flow and impacts on air quality and noise.</p><p> </p><p>Evidence is being taken from twelve core case study schemes which cover a variety of area types from metropolitan and city centre locations to small town and residential areas. Three further case studies cover local authorities that have chosen not to implement 20mph schemes.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","30403 ; 30405","2016-03-17T15:46:50.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458944/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458944/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458944/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-09","Speed Limits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will assess the effect of the introduction of 20 miles per hour speed limits in town centres on congestion.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","30404"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458945","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-17","<p>In June 2014 the Department for Transport commissioned a comprehensive three-year research project into the effects of 20mph limits.</p><p> </p><p>Effects to be assessed include the impacts of 20mph limit schemes on collision and casualty levels, changes in traffic flow and impacts on air quality and noise.</p><p> </p><p>Evidence is being taken from twelve core case study schemes which cover a variety of area types from metropolitan and city centre locations to small town and residential areas. Three further case studies cover local authorities that have chosen not to implement 20mph schemes.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","30403 ; 30404","2016-03-17T15:46:50.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458945/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458945/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458945/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-09","Speed Limits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will assess the effect of the introduction of 20 miles per hour speed limits in (a) town centres and (b) residential areas on pollution.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","30405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458946","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-14","<p>A public hearing is to be held on 18 March which representatives from Highways England will be attending to present their views on the multi-agency response to the M6 incident that occurred on 4 February. In addition, Highways England representatives will be meeting with me on the 22 March to consider a more streamlined approach by agencies when responding to similar incidents in the future.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-14T14:44:18.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458946/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458946/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458946/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-09","M6: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he plans to take to assist the West Midlands Police and Crime Commissioner to establish which lessons Highways England, West Midlands Police and the relevant local highways authorities can learn following the incident on the M6 motorway between junctions five and six on 4 February 2016 and the resulting delays in reopening the motorway.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","30424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458947","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-14","<p>A public hearing is to be held on 18 March which representatives from Highways England will be attending to present their views on the multi-agency response to the M6 incident that occurred on 4 February. In addition, Highways England representatives will be meeting with me on the 22 March to consider a more streamlined approach by agencies when responding to similar incidents in the future.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-14T14:57:17.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458947/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458947/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458947/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-09","M6: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to ensure participation of representatives from Highways England with any public scrutiny held into the incident on the M6 motorway between junctions five and six on 4 February 2016 by the West Midlands Police and Crime Commissioner.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","30425"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458948","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-15","<p>Road projects across the Northern Powerhouse area, including the Cheshire and Warrington Local Enterprise Partnership area, are laid out in page 34 of the Northern Transport Strategy: Spring 2016 Report.</p><p> </p><p>Further details on road schemes are included in the Road Investment Strategy, first published in December 2014 <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/road-investment-strategy#_blank" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/road-investment-strategy</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The Spring 2016 Report also includes potential longer-term transformational opportunities (Trans-Pennine Tunnel).</p><p> </p><p>Transport for the North’s Partnership Board, which approved the Report, includes representation for Cheshire and Warrington Local Enterprise Partnership and for Cheshire West and Chester Council.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-15T15:17:57.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458948/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458948/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458948/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-09","Roads: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to The Northern Transport Strategy: Spring 2016 Report, published on 7 March 2016, how many road projects in (a) Ellesmere Port and Neston constituency, (b) Cheshire West and Chester borough, (c) the Cheshire and Warrington LEP area and (d) the area of the Northern Powerhouse are included in the investment programme.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","30473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458949","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-15","<p>Network Rail’s Plan for Rail in Britain is available at: <a href="http://www.networkrail.co.uk/improvements/indexpage.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.networkrail.co.uk/improvements/indexpage.aspx</a></p><p> </p><p>The Northern Transport Strategy: Spring 2016 Report also includes potential longer-term transformational opportunities (Northern Powerhouse Rail).</p><p> </p><p>Transport for the North’s Partnership Board, which approved the Report, includes representation for Cheshire and Warrington Local Enterprise Partnership and for Cheshire West and Chester Council.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-15T15:23:02.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458949/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458949/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458949/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-09","Railways: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to The Northern Transport Strategy: Spring 2016 Report, published on 7 March 2016, how many rail projects in (a) Ellesmere Port and Neston constituency, (b) Cheshire West and Chester borough, (c) the Cheshire and Warrington LEP area and (d) the area of the Northern Powerhouse are included in the investment programme.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","30474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458950","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-14","<p>The Department for Transport remains in close contact with airlines that were operating flights from the UK to Sharm el-Sheikh. The Government continues to work towards a resumption of direct flights as soon as possible.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-14T15:20:07.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458950/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458950/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458950/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-09","Aviation: Egypt","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what advice his Department has issued to travel companies in relation to the provision of flights to Sharm el-Sheikh; and when he expects those flights to resume.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","30458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458951","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-15","<p>The Northern Transport Strategy Spring Report 2016 sets out progress in developing plans to improve transport connectivity across the North. Transport is important in delivering the Northern Powerhouse agenda.</p><p> </p><p>As yet there has not been a specific assessment of economic benefits to the Ellesmere Port and Neston constituency.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-15T15:26:19.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458951/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458951/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458951/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-09","Transport: Ellesmere Port and Neston","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to The Northern Transport Strategy: Spring 2016 Report, published on 7 March 2016, what assessment he has made of the economic benefit of that strategy to Ellesmere Port and Neston constituency.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","30475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458952","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-15","<p>Rebalancing the economy by creating a Northern Powerhouse is part of our long term economic plan, and an aim that is shared between the Government and the North. Our objective is simple – to allow the North to pool its strengths and become greater than the sum of its parts.</p><p> </p><p>The Northern Transport Strategy aims to support the Northern Powerhouse in achieving its ambitions. At this stage, the Strategy does not outline funding for specific geographical areas, and this is therefore reflected in the Spring Report. In 2014/15, the transport spend per head in the North West of England was £251, and the transport spend for the whole of the North of England was £262.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-15T15:29:32.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458952/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458952/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458952/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-09","Transport: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to The Northern Transport Strategy: Spring 2016 Report, published on 7 March 2016, what estimate his Department has made of public sector investment per capita in (a) Ellesmere Port and Neston constituency, (b) Cheshire West and Chester borough, (c) the Cheshire and Warrington LEP area and (d) the area of the Northern Powerhouse.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","30476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458953","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-16","<p>This information is not held centrally, and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-03-16T12:02:50.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458953/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458953/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458953/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-09","Personal Injury: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate he has made of the number of crash for cash accidents since the implementation of the whiplash reform programme.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","30504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458954","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-17","<p>The Government is exploring a number of options to address the threat from the misuse of laser pens.</p><p> </p><p>There is specific legislation prohibiting the use of laser pens against aircraft. Under the Air Navigation Order (2009), it is an offence to direct or shine any light at any aircraft in flight so as to dazzle or distract the pilot of the aircraft. Anyone found guilty of this offence could be liable to a fine, up to a maximum of £2,500.</p><p> </p><p>It is also an offence to “recklessly or negligently act in a manner to endanger an aircraft, or any person in an aircraft”. Anyone found guilty of this offence could be liable to a fine, up to 5 years imprisonment, or both.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-17T14:21:43.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458954/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458954/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458954/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-09","Aviation: Lasers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he plans to take to safeguard aircraft pilots from potential impairment resulting from the misuse of laser pens.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","30478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458955","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-14","<p>The announcement is a continuation of current government policy, which maintains equality in pension payments for all affected individuals in public services. When the Government consults on the long term solution, it will of course do a full equality impact assessment, should it be necessary.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-03-14T15:20:46.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458955/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458955/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458955/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-09","Public Sector: Guaranteed Minimum Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to HM Treasury's press release of 1 March 2016, on Government one step closer to introducing new State Pension this year, whether an equality impact assessment was carried out before this decision was taken to price protect the Guaranteed Minimum Pension of public sector workers.","true","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","30459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458956","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-14","<p>The Government expects to hold a public consultation later this year.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-03-14T15:22:37.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458956/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458956/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458956/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-09","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to HM Treasury's press release of 1 March 2016, on Government one step closer to introducing new State Pension this year, if he will hold a public consultation on his Department's proposals for pension provision to those people who will reach state pension age after December 2018.","true","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","30460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458957","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-14","<p>Later this year, the Government will consult on giving more responsibility to support older people with care needs to Local Authorities in England and to Wales, including people who, under the current system, would be supported through Attendance Allowance. Work is progressing across government towards this consultation; as part of this process the Government will engage with a wide variety of stakeholders, including claimants and their representatives, to understand the implications of change across a number of issues.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-03-14T17:40:13.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458957/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458957/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458957/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-09","Attendance Allowance: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect of abolition of attendance allowance on people living in rural communities.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","30462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458958","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-14","<p>The Universal Credit (Transitional Provisions) Regulations 2014 make provision for the treatment of Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) claimants when they naturally migrate to UC. Where this occurs claimants who are in receipt of the Work Related-Activity Component in ESA will have the Limited Capability for Work element in UC applied to their UC award from the start of their first UC assessment period and those who are in receipt of the Support Component in ESA will have the Limited Capability for Work and Work-related activity element in UC applied to their UC award from the start of their first UC assessment period.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-03-14T17:01:30.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458958/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458958/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458958/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-09","Universal Credit: Transitional Arrangements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether there will be transitional protection for current claimants of the work-related activity component of employment and support allowance who will be naturally migrated onto universal credit.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","30463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458959","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-14","<p>The number of children in each age group estimated to be in households in receipt of Universal Credit, once fully rolled-out, is:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><br> Age of Child</p></td><td><p><br> Number of Children in Households not receiving UC</p></td><td><p><br> Number of Children in Households receiving UC</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><br> 0-2</p></td><td><p><br> 1,300,000</p></td><td><p><br> 1,430,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><br> 3-5</p></td><td><p><br> 1,090,000</p></td><td><p><br> 1,300,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><br> 6-8</p></td><td><p><br> 1,020,000</p></td><td><p><br> 1,170,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><br> 9-11</p></td><td><p><br> 960,000</p></td><td><p><br> 1,050,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><br> 12-14</p></td><td><p><br> 1,120,000</p></td><td><p><br> 1,000,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><br> 15-18</p></td><td><p><br> 1,310,000</p></td><td><p><br> 1,030,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>The proportion of children in each age group estimated to be in households in receipt of Universal Credit, once fully rolled-out, is:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><br> Age of Child</p></td><td><p><br> Proportion of Children in Households not receiving UC</p></td><td><p><br> Proportion of Children in Households receiving UC</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><br> 0-2</p></td><td><p><br> 48%</p></td><td><p><br> 52%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><br> 3-5</p></td><td><p><br> 46%</p></td><td><p><br> 54%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><br> 6-8</p></td><td><p><br> 47%</p></td><td><p><br> 53%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><br> 9-11</p></td><td><p><br> 48%</p></td><td><p><br> 52%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><br> 12-14</p></td><td><p><br> 53%</p></td><td><p><br> 47%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><br> 15-18</p></td><td><p><br> 56%</p></td><td><p><br> 44%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>These estimates have been made using the Department’s Policy Simulation Model, which is based on the Family Resources Survey (FRS)</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The actual number of children in households receiving Universal Credit once fully rolled-out is dependent on a range of factors including demographic changes and the economic conditions at that time, and therefore these estimates are sensitive to changes in modelling and economic assumptions.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-03-14T17:35:08.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458959/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458959/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458959/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-09","Universal Credit: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate his Department has made of the (a) number and (b) proportion of children in each age group that will be in households in receipt of universal credit once it is fully introduced.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","30466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458960","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-17","<p>We do not hold specific information on the cost of Incapacity Benefit reassessments (IBR) overturned at appeal, as assessment contracts cover all types of assessment, not just IBRs.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-03-17T13:44:19.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458960/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458960/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458960/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-09","Incapacity Benefit: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the amount his Department has spent on re-assessing incapacity benefit claimants who successfully appeal against a finding of non-qualification in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","30433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458961","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-14","<p>We do not issue forecasts of these volumes. The number of claimants of the work-related activity component of employment and support allowance who will be naturally migrated onto universal credit will vary according to a number of factors, such as the economic climate and developments in Government policy.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-03-14T17:33:27.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458961/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458961/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458961/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-09","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate his Department has made of the number of current claimants of the work-related activity component of employment and support allowance who will be naturally migrated onto universal credit in (a) 2017-18, (b) 2018-19 and (c) 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","30464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458963","Attorney General","false","2016-03-16","<p>None of the Law Officers’ Departments employ any security guards directly. Security costs for all departments are instead paid as part of wider contracts for building services.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-03-16T12:26:25.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458963/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458963/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458963/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-03-09","Attorney General: Security Guards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how much security guards in the Law Officers' Departments are paid.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","30579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458964","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-18","<p>This information is not held by the department or its agencies.</p><p>The sector led Supporting Professionalism in Admissions Programme (SPA) has published good practice guidance on admissions for refugees and asylum seekers.</p><p>Through the Vulnerable Persons Resettlement Scheme, the Government is working closely with the UN High Commissioner for Refugees to identify those most at risk and bring them to the UK.</p><p>The UK has been at the forefront of the international response to the Syrian crisis. On 4 February 2016, my right hon. Friend the Prime Minister announced that the UK will more than double our total pledge to the Syria crisis from £1.12 billion to over £2.3 billion. This is our largest ever response to a single humanitarian crisis and means that the UK is one of the largest donors to the Syria crisis.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-03-18T16:00:24.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458964/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458964/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458964/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-09","Scholarships: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many university scholarships have been taken up by Syrian refugees in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Ben Howlett","Bath","Ben Howlett","30498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458965","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-24","<p>The number of officials in the Department of Business, Innovation and Skills, including UKTI, who were absent for reasons relating to stress are shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of people with a stress related absence</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of people with a stress related absence as a % of total headcount</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total number of working days lost due to stress related absence as a % of total absence</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>52</p></td><td><p>1.62%</p></td><td><p>21.8%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>50</p></td><td><p>1.42%</p></td><td><p>14.1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>67</p></td><td><p>1.91%</p></td><td><p>19.6%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>88</p></td><td><p>2.85%</p></td><td><p>24.9%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>84</p></td><td><p>2.68%</p></td><td><p>18.6%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-03-24T15:54:30.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458965/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458965/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458965/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458965/answer/previousversion/51207","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-09","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Sick Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many officials in his Department took sick leave for reasons relating to stress in each of the last five years; and what proportion of (a) his Department's staff and (b) total sick leave such sick leave was in each such year.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","30595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458966","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-21","<p>The Department’s Total Facilities Management (TFM) Contract includes the provision of security guards. The minimum hourly rate for security guards under the TFM contract is £8.48 and on average, annual salary is in the region of £26,500.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-03-21T14:10:49.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458966/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458966/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458966/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-09","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Security Guards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much security guards in his Department are paid.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","30578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458967","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-17","<p>We do not expect the winding down of the Manufacturing Advisory Service will have an impact on businesses receiving services as contractual commitments to existing customers will be honoured, providing all support and related activity is completed by 31 March 2016. Going forward, manufacturers will continue to be able to access expert advice from the private sector from their local Growth Hub.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-17T16:22:14.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458967/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458967/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458967/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-09","Manufacturing Advisory Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of the winding down of the Manufacturing Advisory Service will have on businesses receiving services from that service.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","30487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458968","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-17","<p>The Adjudicator will issue guidance on the Pubs Code. Section 61 of the Small Business, Enterprise and Employment Act 2015 provides details of the guidance the Adjudicator must and may publish regarding the Pubs Code.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-17T16:21:28.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458968/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458968/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458968/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-09","Public Houses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to ensure publicans are made aware of the rights and responsibilities outlined in the Pubs Code, which is due to be published in May 2016.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","30488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458969","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-14","<p>I refer the hon Member to my answer of 9 March to question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-03-02/29561/" target="_blank">29561</a> concerning travel costs incurred by Ministers and officials in relation to the negotiations for the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership. My answer would also apply to cost of overnight accommodation.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-14T11:31:08.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458969/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458969/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458969/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-09","Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much the Government has spent on overnight accommodation for (a) ministers, (b) special advisers and (c) officials relating to the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership negotiation process; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","30540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458970","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-14","<p>As set out in the Model Contract for Special Advisers, full time special advisers are required to work a minimum of 37 hours over a 5 day week, excluding breaks. Copies of the Model Contract are available in the Libraries of the House, and on GOV.UK</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-14T13:29:44.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458970/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458970/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458970/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-03-09","Ministerial Policy Advisers: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the standard office hours are of special advisers.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","30575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458971","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-15","<p>The basic pay range for directly employed London security guards is £19,988 - £24,430 per annum.</p><p>The basic rates of pay for security guards employed by our Facilities Management contractors around the country range from £7.60 per hour to £10.86 per hour, depending on the contract.</p><p>The pay of contracted security guards is above the National Living Wage that is due to be introduced in April.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-15T09:46:52.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458971/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458971/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458971/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-03-09","Cabinet Office: Security Guards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much security guards in his Department are paid.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","30580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458972","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-16","<p>For younger workers, the priority is to secure work and gain valuable experience – something that is reflected in the existing age structure of the National Minimum Wage.</p><p>On 14<sup>th</sup> April my right hon. Friend the Prime Minister announced an increase in the 16-17 year old National Minimum Wage rate by 3.4% (13p) to £4.00 per hour. This is the fastest and largest increase since 2008.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-03-16T15:32:31.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458972/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458972/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458972/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-09","Minimum Wage: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will increase the national minimum wage for under 18s to the same rate as the adult level.","false","Biography information for Richard Arkless","Dumfries and Galloway","Richard  Arkless","30546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458973","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-14","<p>Most recent information from operational systems shows that between 01 March 2013 and 29 February 2016, the Valuation Office Agency took an average (mean) of 17.5 working days to update the Council Tax Valuation Lists for England and Wales with entries for new properties. Out of these, 23,599 cases (representing 5% of the total) took longer than 3 months (defined as 60 working days). Over 99% of all cases are resolved within the first 4 months.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-14T15:25:01.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458973/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458973/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458973/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-09","Council Tax: Valuation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the average time taken is by the Valuation Office Agency to assess new properties to give them a council tax band; and how many such cases have taken longer than three months in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Simon Danczuk","Rochdale","Simon Danczuk","30535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458974","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-14","<p>No details of the number of employees receiving and companies offering Employee Shareholder Status shares are currently available. Similarly, no details of the effect of the tax relief are available.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-14T15:26:21.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458974/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458974/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458974/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-09","Employee Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people have taken up employee shareholder status tax relief in the most recent financial year for which figures are available; and what the effect of that relief was on revenue to the Exchequer in that year.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Chris Leslie","30534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458975","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-14","<p>The security service at HM Treasury is provided by through a service contract, let by the PFI contract landlord for 1 Horse Guards Road (Exchequer Partnership). HM Treasury does not directly employ security guards.</p><p> </p><p>However, the contracted security guards that work within 1 Horse Guards Road are paid £10.80 per hour.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-03-14T15:31:24.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458975/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458975/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458975/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-09","Treasury: Security Guards","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much security guards in his Department are paid.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","30594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458976","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-15","<p>There has been no reduction in Small Business Rate Relief in 2015. The level of Small Business Rate Relief has been doubled since 2010. We estimate that 600,000 ratepayers are benefitting with approximately 400,000 paying no rates at all. My rt hon Friemd, the Chancellor announced at the Autumn Statement that the doubling would continue in 2016-17.</p><p>The doubled level of Small Business Rate Relief ensures that eligible properties with a rateable value of £6,000 or less pay no rates at all. The rate of relief decreases from 100% to 0% for eligible properties with a rateable value between £6,001 and £12,000.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-03-15T12:07:52.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458976/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458976/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458976/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-09","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will estimate the average rise in business rates in (a) Havering and (b) the UK since the reduction of Small Business Rate relief in 2015.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","30553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458977","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-14","<p>Total receipts from General Betting Duty, which includes duty paid on spread bets from financial and non-financial institutions is published here:</p><p><a href="https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/Pages/TaxAndDutybulletins.aspx" target="_blank">https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/Pages/TaxAndDutybulletins.aspx</a></p><p> </p><p>A separate breakdown for revenue accrued from financial spread betting is not available.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-03-14T17:36:01.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458977/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458977/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458977/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-09","Betting: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what revenue accrued to the Exchequer from the financial spread betting gross profits tax in the most recent financial year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Chris Leslie","30533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458978","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-14","<p>The Department holds no such information. It is envisaged that decisions on the remuneration of Combined Authority mayors will be a matter to be decided by the Combined Authority on the basis of recommendations of an independent body.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-03-14T16:23:45.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458978/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458978/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458978/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-09","Mayors: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what information his Department holds on the likely salary of the elected mayor for the West Midlands Combined Authority; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","30541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458979","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-14","<p>Information on business rates and reliefs collected by each local authority are published in the ‘National non-domestic rates collected by councils in England’ statistical series, which are available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/national-non-domestic-rates-collected-by-councils" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/national-non-domestic-rates-collected-by-councils</a></p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-03-14T16:25:58.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458979/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458979/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458979/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-09","Non-domestic Rates: Redcar and Cleveland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many businesses in Redcar and Cleveland have taken part in the retail relief scheme in (a) 2014-15 and (b) 2015-16 to date.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","30542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458980","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-14","<p>We have given local planning authorities a wide range of strong enforcement powers to enable them to tackle unauthorised development or works to listed buildings, including the ability to apply for planning injunctions to prevent actual or apprehended breaches. We consider these powers remain appropriate and have no plans to amend them at this time.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-03-14T16:44:23.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458980/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458980/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458980/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-09","Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to speed up planning enforcement to reduce damage in heritage centres.","false","Biography information for Ben Howlett","Bath","Ben Howlett","30497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458981","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-14","<p>The rate of pay for security guards working in buildings managed by the Department for Communities and Local Government is between £7.20 and £10.34 per hour depending on location, shift pattern, skillset and duration of tenure. Guards in 2 Marsham Street are employed by the Home Office's service provider Bouygues.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-03-14T16:45:28.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458981/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458981/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458981/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-09","Department for Communities and Local Government: Security Guards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much security guards in his Department are paid.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","30581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458982","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-17","<p>DCMS shares premises with other Government Departments - HMRC and DfE - that are responsible for the employment and payment of security staff.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-17T14:03:24.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458982/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458982/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458982/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-09","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Security Guards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how much security guards in his Department are paid.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","30582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458983","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-14","<p>As the Prime Minister stated in his Life Chances speech in January, culture should never be a privilege; it is a birth right that belongs to us all. The Government's Life Chances Strategy will address cultural disenfranchisement directly - ensuring there is real engagement by arts organisations with those who might believe that culture is not for them, meaning that many more children can have the doors opened to their wonderful cultural inheritance.</p><p>The Government has already invested £171 million between 2012-15 in 123 Music Education Hubs to ensure that children aged 5-18 have the opportunity to sing or learn a musical instrument, and a further £75 million of funding was made available for 2015/16. A new, fairer funding system ensures hubs can target money towards pupils who need it most. We have also introduced the In Harmony programme which inspires and transforms the lives of children through community-based orchestral music-making in areas of exceptional deprivation. Both of these programmes offer opportunities for children and young people in the local area to attend after school sessions to learn music. In addition, we have helped create 14 pilot music rehearsal spaces for young people across urban and rural areas of England experiencing multiple deprivation.</p><p>Analysis from the most recent Taking Part Survey shows that in 2014/15, 16.7% of respondents aged 5 -10 years from the upper socio-economic group took part in music lessons outside school compared with 6.6% of those from a lower socio-economic group. Among children aged 11-15, 41.0% from the upper socio-economic group and 31.2% from the lower socio-economic group, have taken part in at least one musical activity outside of school in the last year. Data for regional comparisons of participation are not held by the Department in a reliable format due to small sample sizes.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-14T15:10:49.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458983/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458983/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458983/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-09","Children: Musical Instruments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 4 March 2016 to Question 28838, if he will make a comparative assessment of the proportion of children by (a) region and (b) socio-economic group who learn a musical instrument outside school.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","30524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458984","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-14","<p>My Department, together with the Local Government Association, has set up a Leadership for Libraries Taskforce to help public libraries in England build on good practice and add value for the communities they serve. Thanks to Government funding, 99% of public libraries in England will provide free access to Wi-Fi from May 2016.</p>DCMS has also engaged national Digital Engagement partnerships to help users get online; BT and Barclays have worked together to provide free Wi-Fi in 100 libraries and community centres in deprived areas across England; and Lloyds Banking Group and Halifax Community Bank have piloted a scheme to match local branch staff with libraries to deliver basic digital skills training to adults in the UK.","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-14T15:07:56.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458984/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458984/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458984/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-09","Public Libraries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions he has had with local authorities on changes in the level of availability of library services providing access to digital connectivity for those who do not have access to broadband at home.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","30523"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458985","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-21","<p>DCMS has not conducted an assessment of the effect that commission costs, or their transparency, have on the ability of consumers to achieve value for money when booking hotels online.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett",,"2016-03-21T16:06:19.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458985/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458985/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458985/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-09","Travel Agents: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether his Department has carried out an assessment of the effect of high commission costs and the low transparency of such costs in the online travel agent sector on the ability of consumers to achieve value for money when booking hotels.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","30525"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458986","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-30","<p>My Department has not conducted an assessment of these findings and has no plans to ban such clauses.</p><p> </p><p>Any assessment of the impact of rate parity clauses on competition and consumers falls within the remit of the Competition and Markets Authority (CMA), which is the UK’s primary competition and consumer authority.</p><p>One of the CMA’s predecessors, the Office of Fair Trading (OFT), launched an investigation into alleged resale price maintenance in arrangements between a hotel group and two online travel agents (OTAs), Booking.com and Expedia. The OFT accepted commitments from the OTAs concerned but in September 2014 the Competition Appeal Tribunal partly upheld an appeal by a third party, Skyscanner, and remitted the case back to the CMA for consideration. On 16 September 2015, following a fresh look at the case, the CMA decided to close the investigation on administrative priority grounds. The case closure summary can be found on the CMA’s website.</p><p> </p><p>The CMA keeps these issues under review and is working closely with other national competition authorities and the European Commission to do this.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-03-30T07:53:29.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458986/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458986/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458986/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-09","Holiday Accommodation: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether his Department has conducted an assessment of the findings of the (a) French parliament and (b) German competition authority on the effects of rate parity clauses on competition in the hospitality sector; and what  plans he has to ban rate parity clauses.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","30570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458987","Department for Education","false","2016-03-14","<p>The role of music education hubs is to ensure that every child aged 5-18 has the opportunity to learn a musical instrument through whole-class ensemble teaching.</p><p> </p><p>In 2013/14, Arts Council England data showed that 596,820 pupils learned to play an instrument through whole class ensemble teaching. The full report can be found here: <a href="http://www.artscouncil.org.uk/media/uploads/Music_Education_Hubs_2014_Report_final_March_2015.pdf" target="_blank"><em>http://www.artscouncil.org.uk/media/uploads/Music_Education_Hubs_2014_Report_final_March_2015.pdf</em></a><em>.</em></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-03-14T16:12:00.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458987/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458987/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458987/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-09","Schools: Musical Instruments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 2 March 2016 to Question 28761, what assessment she has made of whether musical education hubs are playing their core role of ensuing that every child aged between 5-18 learns to play a musical instrument.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","30568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458988","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-14","<p>No such estimates have been made by the Ministry of Defence.</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-03-14T16:00:48.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458988/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458988/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458988/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-09","Hebrides Range: Spaceflight","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate he has made of the cost of adding a vertical take-off facility at the Hebrides Range to permit diversification into space ports.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Angus Brendan MacNeil","30567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458989","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-15","<p>Since the start of the 2015-16 session of Parliament to 9 March 2016, 17 written parliamentary questions (PQs) tabled to the Ministry of Defence (MOD) were not answered on the grounds of national security. This figure represents 0.7% of the total number of 2,273 PQs answered by the MOD during that period.</p><p>In seven further PQs, only part of the answer was withheld on national security grounds.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-03-15T16:29:40.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458989/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458989/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458989/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-09","Ministry of Defence: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, on how many occasions his Department has not provided substantive answers to written parliamentary questions on the grounds of national security since the start of the 2015-16 Session; and what proportion of such questions tabled to his Department that number represents.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","30549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458990","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-15","<p>Fast jet aircrew are provided with automatically operating COSPAS-SARSAT compatible Personal Locator Beacons.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-03-15T16:29:01.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458990/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458990/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458990/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-09","Tornado Aircraft: Equipment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the Tornado collision service enquiry report, whether COSPAS-SARSAT compatible Personal Locator Beacons that operate automatically have now been provided to aircrew.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","30511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458991","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-16","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) is currently assessing the viability of dry dock locations where refit work on the Queen Elizabeth Class (QEC)Aircraft Carriers could be carried out. I am withholding the locations being considered as their disclosure would prejudice the commercial interests of the MOD.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-03-16T16:13:07.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458991/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458991/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458991/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-09","Aircraft Carriers: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what locations are being considered for refit work on HMS Queen Elizabeth.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","30510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458992","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-15","<p>In the Ministry of Defence the basic salary for a member of the Ministry of Defence Guard Service who performs security guarding is from £16,253 to £17,760 per annum nationally, and from £17,389 to £19,003 for those based in London.</p><p>In addition, officers may receive up to 20% Regular Shift Allowance, 4% Flexible Rostering Allowance and weekend premiums up to 18%.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-03-15T16:28:05.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458992/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458992/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458992/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-09","Ministry of Defence: Security Guards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much security guards in his Department are paid.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","30583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458993","Department for Education","false","2016-03-14","<p>The rate of pay for security guards working in buildings managed by the Department for Education is between £7.85 and £13.50 depending on location, shift pattern, skillset and duration of tenure.</p><p> </p><p>The Government Equality Office is based within buildings managed by the Department for Education, and therefore the same rates apply.</p><p> </p><p>From 1 April 2016, the rates will be increased to reflect the 2016 Living Wage Foundation rates.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","30588","2016-03-14T15:32:48.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458993/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458993/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458993/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-09","Department for Education: Security Guards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much security guards in her Department are paid.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","30584"
