"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458481","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-03-10","<p>The OpenDefra initiative extends to the whole of Defra including the Rural Payments Agency. The initiative does not extend to the Land Registry.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Rural Land Register, the Land Management System that has replaced it, or other systems maintained by the Rural Payments Agency (RPA), do not look to establish land ownership. The RPA is required to maintain information on land use, in England because land use, and the entitlement to use it, is one of the determining factors in relation to eligibility to claim funds that RPA validates.</p><p> </p><p>We are currently reviewing, the Data Protection Act, confidentiality of information held and intellectual property rights to determine whether information on land use can be released under the open data initiative.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","30217","2016-03-10T15:06:01.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458481/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458481/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458481/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-03-08","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will extend her Department's OpenDefra initiative to the Rural Payments Agency and Land Registry.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","30216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458482","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-03-10","<p>The OpenDefra initiative extends to the whole of Defra including the Rural Payments Agency. The initiative does not extend to the Land Registry.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Rural Land Register, the Land Management System that has replaced it, or other systems maintained by the Rural Payments Agency (RPA), do not look to establish land ownership. The RPA is required to maintain information on land use, in England because land use, and the entitlement to use it, is one of the determining factors in relation to eligibility to claim funds that RPA validates.</p><p> </p><p>We are currently reviewing, the Data Protection Act, confidentiality of information held and intellectual property rights to determine whether information on land use can be released under the open data initiative.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","30216","2016-03-10T15:06:01.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458482/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458482/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458482/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-03-08","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will make maps of UK land ownership available as open data as part of her Department's OpenDefra initiative.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","30217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458483","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-03-16","<p>Government Buying Standards for food and catering services are mandatory for central government and encouraged in the wider public sector. The standards require that all food served must have been produced in compliance with UK legal standards for animal welfare.</p><p> </p><p>To protect the supply of food to central government and other public bodies, including prisons and the military, the only exception is for the procurement of pig and poultry meat. This means that in the event that UK market conditions impose a significant increase in costs that cannot be compensated for by savings elsewhere, pig and poultry meat must as a minimum meet EU standards and the reasons for not applying UK welfare standards must be recorded and signed off by a senior official in the organisation concerned.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-03-16T17:31:58.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458483/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458483/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458483/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-03-08","Meat: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, for what reasons public bodies are permitted to import meat and meat products which due to poor welfare standards would be illegal to produce in the UK.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bingham","High Peak","Andrew Bingham","30218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458484","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-03-15","<p>The salaries of the five highest paid people at the Environment Agency in the last financial year, 2014 to 2015, were published in our annual report and accounts and can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/442886/LIT_10133.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/442886/LIT_10133.pdf</a></p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-03-15T10:56:22.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458484/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458484/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458484/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-03-08","Environment Agency: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the salaries were of the five highest-paid people at the Environment Agency in the last financial year.","false","Biography information for Sir Henry Bellingham","North West Norfolk","Sir Henry Bellingham","30156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458485","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-03-15","<p>As of February 2016, 89% of Defra Senior Civil Servants and 82% of core Defra policy civil servants are based in London.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-03-15T14:41:34.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458485/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458485/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458485/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-03-08","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what proportion of her Department's (a) Senior Civil Servants and (b) core policy civil servants are based in London.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","30310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458486","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-03-11","<p>Defra has spent a total of £11.6 million on biodiversity conservation in the UK Overseas Territories over the last five financial years as follows:</p><p> </p><p>2015/16 - £2.2 million</p><p>2014/15 - £1.6 million</p><p>2013/14 - £2.2 million</p><p>2012/13 - £2.9 million</p><p>2011/12 - £2.7 million</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-03-11T11:30:56.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458486/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458486/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458486/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-03-08","Biodiversity: British Overseas Territories","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much her Department spent on biodiversity conservation in the UK Overseas Territories in each of the last five financial years.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","30361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458487","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-03-11","<p>Defra has been working with other countries in the Oslo and Paris Convention for the Protection of the North East Atlantic (OSPAR) to secure the voluntary phasing out of micro-plastics in personal care and cosmetic products. As part of this, discussions have been held with the British Cosmetics Association, the European trade association Cosmetics Europe, and the British Plastics Federation. In response to these discussions, Cosmetics Europe has recommended that micro-beads should not be used in cosmetics. In addition, many UK cosmetics brands have publically committed to removing micro-beads from their products. Discussions between OSPAR and the industry to achieve the phase out are ongoing.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-03-11T11:01:46.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458487/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458487/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458487/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-03-08","Cosmetics: Plastics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent discussions her Department has held with the cosmetics industry on the voluntary phasing out of micro-plastics in personal care and cosmetic products.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","30360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458488","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-03-11","<p>Defra has funded a project, undertaken by the University of Plymouth, to study the effects of micro-plastics in the marine environment. The project studied whether chemical pollutants stick to plastic particles, whether marine organisms ingest plastic particles and pass them along the food chain, and whether the plastics themselves, or associated chemical pollutants, could cause harm to those organisms. The final report is currently undergoing peer review and is expected to be published shortly.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-03-11T11:03:02.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458488/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458488/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458488/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-03-08","Seas and Oceans: Plastics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what research her Department has funded into the effects of micro-plastics in the marine environment in the last 12 months; what the terms of reference are for such research; what institution is undertaking that research; when such research will report; and if she will make it her policy to publish the results of such research.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","30362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458489","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-03-11","<p>I welcome the Dogs Trust initiative to pay the quarantine costs of dogs and puppies identified at Dover as being not compliant to enter Great Britain under the EU Pet Travel Scheme. Since 2 December 2015, 108 puppies have been licensed into the quarantine facilities, mainly due to concerns that puppies were under the minimum age for travelling.</p><p>The Animal and Plant Health Agency will carry out an assessment of the effectiveness of the initiative following its conclusion.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-03-11T11:05:06.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458489/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458489/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458489/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-03-08","Dogs: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the Dogs Trust pilot quarantine on disrupting the illegal importation of puppies under the Pet Travel Scheme.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","30363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458490","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-03-16","<p>The Government is committed to providing food produced to British standards or their equivalent in all its canteens, restaurants and cafeterias by the end of this Parliament. Defra is working closely with other Departments and businesses to implement Dr Peter Bonfield’s Plan for Public Procurement of Food, including a balanced scorecard. The Ministry of Justice recently launched a tender for supplying food to prisons, worth £500m, which requires bids to use the balanced scorecard. Their current supplier has agreed that the 30 million portions of UHT milk served in prisons each year will be sourced from UK producers. All new Central Government food and catering contracts will use the balanced scorecard approach.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-03-16T17:29:35.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458490/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458490/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458490/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-03-08","Food: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what progress has been made on implementation of the recommendations of the Bonfield report on public procurement of food; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bingham","High Peak","Andrew Bingham","30380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458491","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-16","<p>The United Kingdom co-sponsored the General Assembly resolution “Building a peaceful and better world through sport and the Olympic ideal”, which calls for Member States to observe the Olympic Truce – a cessation of hostilities around the Olympic Games – within the framework of the Charter of the United Nations, and to promote peace through sport. As a permanent member of the United Nations Security Council, the UK already works to uphold the UN Charter and its commitment to the maintenance of international peace and security.</p><p>For the 2012 Olympic Games in London the UK was the first ever nation to get all 193 UN Member States to sign the Olympic Truce. We are actively involved in building links between countries through sport. HM Government supported the successful London 2012 International Inspiration programme that reached 25m children in twenty countries through the power of sport and continues to support a range of other related initiatives around the world such as the British Council's Premier Skills and Try Rugby programmes. Looking ahead to next year's IAAF World Athletics Championships due to be hosted in London, the Government, through UK Sport, is supporting LEAP (Leadership and Excellence in Athletics Programme) which aims to develop youth athletics in a number of countries around the world.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-03-16T17:17:07.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458491/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458491/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458491/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-08","Brazil: Olympic Games","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what plans the Government has to implement the recent UN General Assembly Resolution on an Olympic truce during the Rio 2016 Olympic and Paralympic Games.","false","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter","30348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458492","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-11","<p>The Pitcairn Island Government is currently in the process of tendering for a new freight and passenger service. We will stress to them the importance of the need for best practice for biosecurity and waste disposal.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-03-11T13:20:59.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458492/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458492/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458492/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-08","Pitcairn Islands: Shipping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will ensure that the new ship contract agreed for the Pitcairn Islands supply run will include best practice stipulations regarding biosecurity and waste disposal.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","30359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458493","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-15","<p>a) The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) has 143 Senior Civil Servants based in London (representing 40% of the Department’s Senior Civil Servants);</p><p>b) The FCO has 2491 Civil Servants based in London (representing 54% of the Department’s Civil Servants).</p><p>These are headcount figures as at 31st December 2015.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-03-15T14:46:52.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458493/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458493/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458493/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-08","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what proportion of his Department's (a) Senior Civil Servants and (b) core policy civil servants are based in London.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","30311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458494","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-11","<p>As outlined in our response to PQ 29560 the latest available public figures on the number of Daesh fighters in Iraq and Syria come from the US. These put the number at approximately 19,000 – 25,000, compared to 20,000 – 31,000 fighters in 2014.</p><p>Our current estimate for the number of Daesh fighters in Libya is between 3,000 – 6,000. We do not have earlier estimates from which we could extrapolate a trend. The vast majority of Daesh fighters in Libya are foreigners rather than Libyans. While some Daesh figures have called for foreign fighters to go to Libya rather than Iraq/Syria, we have not seen any evidence to suggest this has happened.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-03-11T14:05:15.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458494/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458494/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458494/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-08","Middle East: Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 7 March 2016 to Question 29560, what assessment he has made of trends in the number of active Daesh fighters in (a) Iraq, (b) Libya and (c) Syria in each of the last 24 months; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","30296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458495","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-11","<p>We do not hold figures for the numbers of Yezidi civilians who are being held by Daesh forces. The situation is desperate for many communities within Syria and Iraq. We condemn in the strongest terms the targeting and persecution by Daesh of Yezidis, Christians, Muslims and all other communities.</p><p>Ultimately, the best way of preventing future atrocities is to defeat Daesh and its violent ideology. That’s why the UK is playing a leading role in the Global Coalition of 66 countries and international organisations committed to tackling Daesh.</p><p>We are also using our aid budget to alleviate the humanitarian suffering caused by Daesh and the wider conflict in Syria. The UK has now pledged a total of over £2.3 billion, our largest ever response to a single humanitarian crisis. The funding is providing support, such as food, medical care and relief items, to over a million people including those targeted by Daesh. This includes life-saving maternal and child health-care, child protection services, and specialized support for those who have escaped Daesh’s terror.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-03-11T14:25:41.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458495/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458495/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458495/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-08","Islamic State: Yazidis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent estimate he has made of how many Yazidi civilians are held by Daesh forces in Iraq and Syria.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","30304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458496","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-11","<p>Our Embassy in Tel Aviv and our Consulate General in Jerusalem give us regular updates on the current situation in Israel and the Occupied Palestinian Territories. These updates include reports on rockets being fired from the Gaza Strip into the sea; any rocket fire from Gaza into Israel; and any retaliatory Israeli air strikes on Gaza. However they do not keep a record of the numbers, but according to UN figures, in January 2016 a total of three rockets were fired into Israel by Gazan militant groups.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-03-11T14:27:53.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458496/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458496/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458496/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-08","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent reports he has received of rocket fire into Israel from Gaza.","false","Biography information for Paul Scully","Sutton and Cheam","Paul Scully","30247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458497","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-16","<p>We are concerned about the treatment of refugees and asylum seekers in Thailand. We continue to work with the UNHCR in Thailand on a wide range of refugee issues. However, Thailand is not a signatory to the 1951 UN Convention on Refugees. Once any form of legal immigration status expires, refugees and asylum claimants may be deemed to be in Thailand illegally even if they have registered with the UNHCR. Nonetheless, we have pressed the Thai authorities to apply international humanitarian norms and standards when handling these vulnerable groups. We are also working with the Thai authorities to improve conditions of detention.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-03-16T16:54:36.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458497/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458497/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458497/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-08","Thailand: Christianity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he is making to (a) the UN and (b) his Thailand counterpart on the detention of Pakistani Christians fleeing religious persecution in Thailand despite being UN-registered asylum seekers.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","30233"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458498","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-11","<p>We have been clear that we want to see US presence continue. No decisions have yet been made about whether and when to have discussions with the US about their continued presence on Diego Garcia.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-03-11T12:58:48.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458498/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458498/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458498/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-08","Diego Garcia: Military Bases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when he expects discussions to begin with the US government on extending the lease for the military base on Diego Garcia.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","30252"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458499","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-11","<p>Religious freedom in Nigeria is protected by the Nigerian Constitution. Boko Haram seeks to undermine this constitutional provision by attacking all Nigerians who do not subscribe to its extremist views. It has committed atrocities against people of all faiths, including Christians and Muslims, with the majority of those killed having been Muslims. We regularly discuss with the Nigerian Government at the highest levels our concern about the threat Boko Haram poses to communities of different faiths and ethnicities. We will continue to work with the Nigerian Government, non-governmental organisations and civil society to improve the security situation and human rights for all in Nigeria.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-03-11T13:06:58.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458499/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458499/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458499/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-08","Nigeria: Christianity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with representatives of the Nigerian government on the persecution of Christians in Nigeria.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","30187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458500","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-16","<p>We are aware of reports of the execution of General Ri Yong-gil, the Chief of Staff of the Korean People’s Army, on Wednesday 10 February 2016. Due to the closed nature of the regime in the Democratic People’s Republic of Korea (DPRK), we cannot verify the accuracy of these reports. The UK, working with the EU and Japan, has ensured that annual UN resolutions consistently call on the DPRK to end its use of the death penalty and adhere to international standards on judicial procedures. We also use our diplomatic relations to raise our concerns directly with North Korea officials in London and Pyongyang.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-03-16T16:43:51.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458500/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458500/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458500/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-08","North Korea: Capital Punishment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his North Korean counterpart on the reported recent execution of Ri Yong-gil in that country.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","30163"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458501","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-16","<p>We continue to monitor specific cases and regularly underline the importance of freedom of expression and all fundamental freedoms as part of our broader dialogue with the Turkish government. We welcomed the EU Commission’s Annual Progress Report on Turkey, released on 10 November, which highlighted the need for further reforms from Turkey in these areas. As a friend and ally, we urge the Turkish government to uphold the right of media to operate without restriction. The Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron) did so on 7 March when he met Turkey’s Prime Minister, Ahmet Davutoğlu, and underlined the importance of protections for a free press and human rights in Turkey. The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) set out the UK’s concerns on freedom of expression when he met his Turkish counterpart on 12 March. I also discussed media freedoms and rule of law issues when I met Turkey’s Deputy Prime Minister on 12 March.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-03-16T16:56:14.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458501/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458501/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458501/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-08","Turkey: Freedom of Expression","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he has made representations to the Turkish government on the takeover of the Zaman newspaper and restrictions on press freedom and freedom of speech in Turkey.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","30203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458502","Department of Health","false","2016-03-11","<p>As announced by the Chancellor in the Spending Review in November 2015, the Government has committed to remove the cap on the number of students studying nursing, midwifery and the allied health professions from 1 August 2017. This will enable universities to offer up to 10,000 new training places for students to start these courses in this Parliament.</p><p> </p><p>This reflects estimates on the level of unmet demand for places in the current system where, as an example, for nursing, around two out of three nursing applicants who currently apply for a place are turned down.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is working with health and higher education delivery organisations to determine an appropriate baseline as part of implementing the reforms.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","30185","2016-03-11T12:40:09.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458502/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458502/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458502/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Allied Health Professions: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 4 February 2016 to Question 26014, what the baseline year is for the commitment to train 10,000 more nurses, midwives and other allied health professionals over the course of the current Parliament.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","30204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458503","Department of Health","false","2016-03-11","<p>The publication date for the public consultation has yet to be finalised but we expect the consultation to be published before the end of March.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-03-11T12:43:05.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458503/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458503/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458503/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he expects to publish the consultation proposals to remove the NHS bursary.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","30206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458504","Department of Health","false","2016-03-15","<p>The configuration of services, including decisions to establish inflammatory arthritis clinics, is a matter for the local National Health Service.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-03-15T11:10:12.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458504/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458504/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458504/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Arthritis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to introduce inflammatory arthritis clinics across the UK.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","30196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458505","Department of Health","false","2016-03-15","<p>The Care Quality Commission (CQC) is the independent regulator for health and adult social care. The CQC is responsible for its own staffing requirements, including any decisions on contracts around the supplying of experts by experience for its inspections of providers.</p><p> </p><p>In line with Cabinet Office approvals processes, the Department:</p><p> </p><p>- gave approval for the CQC to invite tenders for the Experts by Experience programme; and</p><p>- having sought and received clarification of the business case from the CQC, the department approved the business case, to enable the CQC to proceed with finalising new contracts for Experts by Experience.</p><p> </p><p>Regulatory impact assessments for the Experts by Experience programme were carried out by the CQC as part of the development of the new regulatory framework in 2014.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-03-15T11:16:49.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458505/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458505/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458505/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","NHS: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether the Care Quality Commission has conducted an impact assessment of the proposed changes to the contract of Experts by Experience.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","30197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458506","Department of Health","false","2016-03-16","<p>The Care Quality Commission (CQC) is the independent regulator of health and adult social care in England. The CQC has provided the following information.</p><p>The cost of recruiting for the post of National Guardian was £61,300 (including VAT) and the costs of recruitment were borne equally across NHS Trust Development Authority, NHS England, the independent regulator of NHS foundation trusts (Monitor) and the CQC. This figure includes the cost of executive search, advertising and minimal individual expenses.</p><p>The recruitment services for the role were provided by Russell Reynolds Associates. Due to the short duration in post of the person appointed the CQC does not envisage a fee being levied to support the recruitment of a replacement.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-03-16T16:15:32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458506/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458506/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458506/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Care Quality Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the cost was of the recruitment process for the post of National Guardian in the Care Quality Commission.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","30237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458507","Department of Health","false","2016-03-11","<p>Two organisations have withdrawn from the Responsibility Deal since May 2015.</p><p> </p><p>Information about the Deal and the partners that have signed up to it can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://responsibilitydeal.dh.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://responsibilitydeal.dh.gov.uk/</a></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-03-11T13:22:56.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458507/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458507/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458507/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many organisations have withdrawn from the Responsibility Deal since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","30214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458508","Department of Health","false","2016-03-15","<p>Where local National Health Service trusts have identified local requirements for improving the capture of clinical and administrative information, including those in outpatient departments, funds have been made available to NHS providers for electronic systems through the Integrated Digital Care Fund and the South Local Clinical Systems Programmes. These include patient administration, patient record, and document management systems which will help the recording and accessing data at the point of care.</p><p> </p><p>The National Information Board’s Personalised Health and Care 2020 framework, published in November 2014, supports further action to improve systems for capturing, coding and integrating data from NHS outpatient departments.</p><p> </p><p>Work being taken forward under Personalised Health and Care 2020 includes:</p><p>― improving the recording and accessing of data at the point of care - around £1.4 billion of the recently announced £4.2 billion investment in NHS technology over the next five years will support the better collection of data and the commitment to become paper-free at the point of care;</p><p>― work to examine ways in which outpatient departments can improve the way they capture activity data using standardised coding terminology (SNOMED CT), so that it can be made available to other parts of a hospital, and support reporting and clinical audit; and</p><p>― a focus on the integration of information within and between care settings, starting with impatient transfers of care, and expanding in 2017-18 to cover other care domains, including the exchange of outpatient information between acute trusts and general practitioner surgeries.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-03-15T12:24:27.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458508/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458508/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458508/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Out-patients: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to improve the systems for capturing, coding and integrating data from NHS outpatient clinics.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","30238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458509","Department of Health","false","2016-03-16","<p>Public Health England (PHE) is responsible for collecting cancer data to support national cancer registration in England and recognises the importance of collecting data on recurrent breast cancer.</p><p>At present pilot work in acute trusts has improved the reporting for breast cancer recurrence and metastasis to the National Cancer Registration Service but the uptake has been slow and the data is not complete. Further work is being scoped by NHS England and PHE based on the recommendation in the recent Independent Cancer Taskforce report to establish robust surveillance systems to collect this data on all cancers.</p><p>Data on the number of people diagnosed with secondary breast cancer is not currently available.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","30222 ; 30225","2016-03-16T16:52:41.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458509/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458509/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458509/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Breast Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people were diagnosed with secondary breast cancer in the last three months.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","30221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458510","Department of Health","false","2016-03-11","<p>As announced by the Chancellor in the Spending Review in November 2015, the Government has committed to remove the cap on the number of students studying nursing, midwifery and the allied health professions from 1 August 2017. This will enable universities to offer up to 10,000 new training places for students to start these courses in this Parliament.</p><p> </p><p>This reflects estimates on the level of unmet demand for places in the current system where, as an example, for nursing, around two out of three nursing applicants who currently apply for a place are turned down.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is working with health and higher education delivery organisations to determine an appropriate baseline as part of implementing the reforms.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","30204","2016-03-11T12:40:08.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458510/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458510/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458510/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Nurses: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 22 January 2016 to Question 23092, how the figure of 10,000 for the number of additional training places universities will be able to provide by the end of the current Parliament was calculated.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","30185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458511","Department of Health","false","2016-03-11","<p>Health Education England (HEE) published its <em>HEE commissioning and investment plan for 2016/17</em> in December 2015 and HEE local team plans will be published by the end of March 2016.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-03-11T12:36:36.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458511/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458511/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458511/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","NHS: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 4 February 2016 to Question 26002, on NHS: training, when Health Education England will publish the local plans.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","30186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458512","Department of Health","false","2016-03-11","<p>The Childhood Obesity Strategy will be launched in the summer.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-03-11T12:28:21.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458512/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458512/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458512/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Children: Obesity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when his Department plans to publish its childhood obesity strategy.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","30166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458513","Department of Health","false","2016-03-11","<p>The Department own three buildings that are empty or vacant; all are part of the Department’s retained estate.</p><p> </p><p>They are the former Harperbury Hospital, the former Little Plumstead Hospital and 100 Churchill Rd, Wisbech.</p><p> </p><p>The future use of all sites is subject of active consideration, which is at different stages.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-03-11T12:59:34.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458513/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458513/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458513/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Department of Health: Empty Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what buildings owned by his Department are empty or vacant.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","30167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458514","Department of Health","false","2016-03-11","<p>The proportion of office space owned or occupied by the Department and its executive agencies which is currently unused is (a) 0% and (b) 1.37 %.</p><p> </p><p>The Department’s executive agencies are Public Health England and the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency. The vacant space is leased by the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency and will be released on 31 March 2016.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-03-11T13:05:36.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458514/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458514/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458514/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Department of Health: Empty Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of office space owned or occupied by (a) his Department and (b) its executive agencies is currently unused.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","30168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458515","Department of Health","false","2016-03-11","<p>Information on the proportion of student nurses who have childcare responsibilities is not collected by the Department.</p><p> </p><p>The table below shows the total number and percentage of student nurses who were in receipt of a National Health Service bursary and also claimed an allowance in respect to potential childcare responsibilities in 2014/15.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Award Element</p></td><td><p>Number of student nurses</p></td><td><p>Percentage of total student nurses<sup>1</sup></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Childcare Allowance</p></td><td><p>6,881</p></td><td><p>11.4%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Parent Learning Allowance</p></td><td><p>12,451</p></td><td><p>20.7%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Dependents Allowance (Child Element)</p></td><td><p>11,533</p></td><td><p>19.1%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Source:</em> NHS Business Services Authority</p><p><sup> 1</sup>Students may be in receipt of one or a combination of all three allowances</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-03-11T12:47:04.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458515/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458515/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458515/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Nurses: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate his Department has made of the proportion of student nurses who have childcare responsibilities.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","30151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458516","Department of Health","false","2016-03-16","<p>There will be two national ‘Be Clear on Cancer’ campaigns in 2016-17. The decision on which cancers these campaigns will focus on will be informed by a steering group, whose members include primary and secondary care clinicians, analysts and key voluntary sector organisations. A number of factors are taken into account when deciding which campaigns to run, including all available evaluation data. A second national oesophago-gastric campaign will be considered alongside the other existing campaigns.</p><p> </p><p>PHE is analysing cancer waiting times data and campaign tracking research and it is expected that the first national oesophago-gastric cancer (1st wave) interim report will be published this summer.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","30148","2016-03-16T12:13:40.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458516/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458516/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458516/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Oesophageal Cancer: Health Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department plans to run a second Be Clear on Cancer campaign on oesophago-gastric cancers.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","30147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458517","Department of Health","false","2016-03-16","<p>There will be two national ‘Be Clear on Cancer’ campaigns in 2016-17. The decision on which cancers these campaigns will focus on will be informed by a steering group, whose members include primary and secondary care clinicians, analysts and key voluntary sector organisations. A number of factors are taken into account when deciding which campaigns to run, including all available evaluation data. A second national oesophago-gastric campaign will be considered alongside the other existing campaigns.</p><p> </p><p>PHE is analysing cancer waiting times data and campaign tracking research and it is expected that the first national oesophago-gastric cancer (1st wave) interim report will be published this summer.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","30147","2016-03-16T12:13:40.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458517/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458517/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458517/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Oesophageal Cancer: Health Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when his Department's evaluation of the Be Clear on Cancer campaign for oesophago-gastric cancers will be published.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","30148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458518","Department for Education","false","2016-03-16","<p>Young carers are this country’s unsung heroes, selflessly providing support for the people they love. Yet, for the most noble of reasons, they can often overlook their own needs. This government recognises the enormous contribution that young carers make and that’s why we are improving support for carers of all ages and developing a new cross-government carers strategy.</p><p> </p><p>No official assessment has been made of the savings to the public purse of young carers supporting their families.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-03-16T17:51:16.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458518/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458518/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458518/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-08","Carers: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate her Department has made of the savings to the public purse of young carers supporting their families instead of the local authority doing so.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","30140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458519","Department of Health","false","2016-03-11","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-03-11T12:57:35.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458519/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458519/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458519/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","General Practitioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many GP practices have a mental health specialist.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","30260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458520","Department of Health","false","2016-03-11","<p>No estimate has been made of the number and proportion of clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) that commission mental health services specifically for older adults. All CCGs will have a cohort of older adults for whom there is mental health services provision. In recent years there has been a trend towards ageless mental health services.</p><p> </p><p>However, one of the recommendations in the Mental Health Taskforce report <em>The Five Year Forward View for Mental Health </em>published by NHS England in February this year is that bespoke older adult services should be the preferred model until such time that general adult mental health services can be shown to provide age-appropriate care. <em> </em></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-03-11T12:56:53.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458520/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458520/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458520/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Mental Health Services: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the (a) number and (b) proportion of clinical commissioning groups that commission mental health services specifically for older adults.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","30264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458521","Department of Health","false","2016-03-11","<p>The Department does not hold information on how many designated health places of safety for under-18s there are in each clinical commissioning group.</p><p> </p><p>The Care Quality Commission (CQC) has produced a map of the location of designated health-based places of safety in England for people detained under section 136 of the Mental Health Act. The CQC has also published a table that breaks this information down by local authority. This information can be found at the following CQC website:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><a href="http://www.cqc.org.uk/content/map-health-based-places-safety-0#howto" target="_blank">http://www.cqc.org.uk/content/map-health-based-places-safety-0#howto</a></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-03-11T12:55:46.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458521/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458521/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458521/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Compulsorily Detained Psychiatric Patients: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many designated health places of safety for under-18s there are in each clinical commissioning group.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","30263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458522","Department of Health","false","2016-03-11","<p>In the November 2015 Spending Review, the Government announced changes to how healthcare student places will be funded. The policy intention of the reforms is to change the funding system for pre-registration undergraduate and postgraduate courses in nursing, midwifery and allied health subjects. From 1 August 2017, these courses will be funded through the standard student loans system; and will not receive Health Education England funding for tuition and students or an National Heaslth Service bursary. The changes will apply to new students only.</p><p> </p><p>Child Psychotherapists courses are not included in the policy intention for these reforms as they do not attract funding through the NHS Bursary Scheme.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-03-11T12:42:09.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458522/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458522/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458522/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Psychiatry: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the potential effects of changes to training funding on the numbers of child psychotherapists training and qualifying as part of the NHS workforce.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","30262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458523","Department of Health","false","2016-03-16","<p>Public Health England (PHE) is responsible for collecting cancer data to support national cancer registration in England and recognises the importance of collecting data on recurrent breast cancer.</p><p>At present pilot work in acute trusts has improved the reporting for breast cancer recurrence and metastasis to the National Cancer Registration Service but the uptake has been slow and the data is not complete. Further work is being scoped by NHS England and PHE based on the recommendation in the recent Independent Cancer Taskforce report to establish robust surveillance systems to collect this data on all cancers.</p><p>Data on the number of people diagnosed with secondary breast cancer is not currently available.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","30221 ; 30225","2016-03-16T16:52:41.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458523/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458523/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458523/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Breast Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to improve his Department's collection of data for secondary breast cancer.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","30222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458524","Department of Health","false","2016-03-16","<p>The independent Cancer Taskforce published its report, Achieving World-Class Cancer Outcomes, in July last year, recognising the importance of access to clinical nurse specialists or other key workers for patients with all types of cancer.</p><p>NHS England is currently working with partners across the health system to determine how best to implement the recommendations of the Cancer Taskforce and has appointed Cally Palmer CBE (Chief Executive of the Royal Marsden) as National Cancer Director to lead on implementation, as well as new cancer vanguards to redesign care and patient experience. She has set up a new Cancer Transformation Board to implement the strategy, which met for the first time on 25 January. There will also be a Cancer Advisory Group, chaired by Sir Harpal Kumar, to oversee and scrutinise the work of the Transformation Board.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-03-16T12:39:07.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458524/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458524/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458524/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Breast Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to ensure that secondary breast cancer patients have access to a clinical nurse specialist as part of their care.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","30223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458525","Department of Health","false","2016-03-14","<p>The number of cancer clinical nurse specialists working in the National Health Service is not collected centrally.</p><p> </p><p>It is for local NHS organisations with their knowledge of the healthcare needs of their local population to invest in training for specialist skills and to deploy specialist nurses.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-03-14T11:20:22.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458525/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458525/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458525/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Cancer: Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many cancer clinical nurse specialists were working in the NHS in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","30224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458526","Department of Health","false","2016-03-16","<p>Public Health England (PHE) is responsible for collecting cancer data to support national cancer registration in England and recognises the importance of collecting data on recurrent breast cancer.</p><p>At present pilot work in acute trusts has improved the reporting for breast cancer recurrence and metastasis to the National Cancer Registration Service but the uptake has been slow and the data is not complete. Further work is being scoped by NHS England and PHE based on the recommendation in the recent Independent Cancer Taskforce report to establish robust surveillance systems to collect this data on all cancers.</p><p>Data on the number of people diagnosed with secondary breast cancer is not currently available.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","30221 ; 30222","2016-03-16T16:52:41.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458526/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458526/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458526/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Breast Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to ensure hospital trusts routinely collect and submit data on secondary breast cancer.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","30225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458527","Department of Health","false","2016-03-11","<p>On 3 December 2015 the Education Secretary announced 22 pilot areas across the country would develop better joint working arrangements to support timely and appropriate referrals to services and implement a joint training programme for named contacts in Child and Adolescent Mental Health Services and schools.</p><p> </p><p>To take forward these actions, the Department and NHS England are working together to test the named lead approach and to trial a joint training programme for them. The training workshops element of the pilot began in November 2015 and it is expected that all of the workshops will be delivered by the middle of March 2016.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-03-11T13:23:44.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458527/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458527/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458527/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Schools: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many co-commissioning pilots aimed at improving clear access routes between schools and specialist mental health services have been launched in each (a) year since 2010 and (b) month of 2015-16 to date.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","30261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458528","Department of Health","false","2016-03-11","<p>Health Education England (HEE) is responsible for advising the Government on the total number of medical school places and for commissioning postgraduate medical education. This aims to ensure that we have a National Health Service workforce in the right numbers, with the right skills, values and behaviour to respond to the current and future needs of patients. It takes around 5 years of medical school (undergraduate) and a year of training to become a registered doctor and a further 4 to 11 years of training to specialise in General Practice or hospital specialities.</p><p> </p><p>There are currently over 50,000 doctors in training in England according to Health Education England’s Workforce Plan (2015/16) for England.</p><p> </p><p>The latest monthly workforce statistics for November 2015 published by the Health and Social Care Information Centre show that there are 106,124 full-time equivalent doctors currently employed in the NHS in England which is an increase of 10,703 (11.2%) since May 2010.</p><p> </p><p>The Department and the Higher Education Funding Council for England (HEFCE) share responsibility for determining the medical and dental school undergraduate intakes in England. The Department (via HEE) is responsible for determining overall numbers, and HEFCE has responsibility for the individual distribution to medical and dental schools. Historically places have broadly ben allocated for each institution the same as the previous year, so as to keep stability in recruitment, to help institutions to plan for their intake and in order to meet the national target.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","30298","2016-03-11T14:35:39.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458528/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458528/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458528/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Doctors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the gap is between the number of available and required trained doctors.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","30297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458529","Department of Health","false","2016-03-11","<p>Health Education England (HEE) is responsible for advising the Government on the total number of medical school places and for commissioning postgraduate medical education. This aims to ensure that we have a National Health Service workforce in the right numbers, with the right skills, values and behaviour to respond to the current and future needs of patients. It takes around 5 years of medical school (undergraduate) and a year of training to become a registered doctor and a further 4 to 11 years of training to specialise in General Practice or hospital specialities.</p><p> </p><p>There are currently over 50,000 doctors in training in England according to Health Education England’s Workforce Plan (2015/16) for England.</p><p> </p><p>The latest monthly workforce statistics for November 2015 published by the Health and Social Care Information Centre show that there are 106,124 full-time equivalent doctors currently employed in the NHS in England which is an increase of 10,703 (11.2%) since May 2010.</p><p> </p><p>The Department and the Higher Education Funding Council for England (HEFCE) share responsibility for determining the medical and dental school undergraduate intakes in England. The Department (via HEE) is responsible for determining overall numbers, and HEFCE has responsibility for the individual distribution to medical and dental schools. Historically places have broadly ben allocated for each institution the same as the previous year, so as to keep stability in recruitment, to help institutions to plan for their intake and in order to meet the national target.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","30297","2016-03-11T14:35:40.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458529/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458529/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458529/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","St George's Hospital Medical School","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, for what reasons St George's Medical School is capped at 259 student doctors each year.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","30298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458530","Department of Health","false","2016-03-16","<p>The Southampton City Primary Care Hub scheme supports 269,875 patients from 33 general practitioner (GP) practices, providing them with access to improved services across Southampton via six hubs. The first of these six hubs opened in June 2015 and offers GP and Healthcare Assistant appointments from 6:30pm-8:00pm in the evenings and 8:00am-8:00pm at the weekends. Two further hubs went live in September and a further two early January 2016 as part of a phased rollout.</p><p>Information technology offerings from the hubs will feature e-Consultations and e-Feedback for patients which will be phased across the hubs in 2016. Since September 2015, the scheme has also been offering patients a physiotherapy service delivering primary care physio in the evenings and at weekends, alongside a pathway redesign to support GPs as first contact for patients with musculoskeletal problems.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-03-16T12:34:09.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458530/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458530/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458530/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","General Practitioners: Southampton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he plans to take to ensure that seven-day GP services are provided in Southampton.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","30274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458531","Department of Health","false","2016-03-16","<p>The information is not collected centrally and no estimate has been made.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-03-16T12:35:46.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458531/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458531/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458531/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","St Thomas' Hospital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the effect on cost and on bed capacity of delayed hospital discharge at the Lane Fox Respiratory Unit at St Thomas' Hospital, London; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","30281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458532","Department of Health","false","2016-03-15","<p>There are several different treatments available for the management of lipoedema such as compression therapy, exercise and massage. There is limited evidence on the efficacy of liposuction for the treatment of lipoedema, and it is not routinely available on the National Health Service.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-03-15T11:19:17.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458532/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458532/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458532/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Lipoedema","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will implement a treatment pathway for people who suffer from lipoedema to allow such people to receive liposuction on the NHS.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","30284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458533","Department of Health","false","2016-03-11","<p>Spend as a percentage of gross domestic product (GDP) is usually reported on a United Kingdom basis. HM Treasury publishes UK health spend figures as a percentage of GDP which are shown below. Note this excludes private health expenditure.</p><p> </p><p>Spend on health in UK as % of GDP –</p><p>1996/97 – 5.0%</p><p>1997/98 – 5.0%</p><p>1998/99 – 5.0%</p><p>1999/00 – 5.0%</p><p>2000/01 – 5.2%</p><p>2001/02 – 5.6%</p><p>2002/03 – 5.8%</p><p>2003/04 – 6.2%</p><p>2004/05 – 6.5%</p><p>2005/06 – 6.7%</p><p>2006/07 – 6.6%</p><p>2007/08 – 6.7%</p><p>2008/09 – 7.2%</p><p>2009/10 – 7.8%</p><p>2010/11 – 7.6%</p><p>2011/12 – 7.4%</p><p>2012/13 – 7.5%</p><p>2013/14 – 7.5%</p><p>2014/15 – 7.4%</p><p> </p><p><em>Source:</em> Table 4.4 HMT, Public Expenditure Statistical Analyses 2015.</p><p> </p><p>The Spending Review settlement, delivered by the Chancellor on 25 November, set the Department’s overall budget for the remaining years of the parliament and the level of funding that will be available to the National Health Service. It set absolute spending totals, not spending as a percentage of GDP, providing certainty for financial planning over the period. The Department has not therefore made forecasts for health spending as a share of GDP for future years.</p><p> </p><p>GDP figures are calculated on an economy wide basis, so GDP figures for England are not available to calculate spend on health care in England as a share of English GDP.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-03-11T13:04:25.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458533/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458533/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458533/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of gross domestic product (GDP) has been spent on health care in (a) England and (b) the UK in each year since 1997; and what estimate he has made of the proportion of GDP that will be spent on health care over the next five years.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","30292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458534","Department of Health","false","2016-03-11","<p>On the 11 February 2016 my Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State made an oral statement, Official Report, columns 1763-1765 in which he announced that he would proceed with the introduction of a new national contract for doctors in training, following advice that there was no realistic prospect of reaching agreement with the British Medical Association.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State will carefully consider the draft final terms of such a contract in light of any applicable duties and the Family Test.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-03-11T12:44:13.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458534/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458534/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458534/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Junior Doctors: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the outcome was of his Department's application of the Family Test to the decision to impose a new contract on junior doctors.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","30293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458535","Department of Health","false","2016-03-11","<p>The publication General and Personal Medical Services contains the aggregated number of registered patients at 30 September each year, but the average over the course of the year is not held centrally. Tables for each of the last 15 years have been placed in the Library. They provide snap-shot data as at 30 September for that year.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-03-11T12:54:50.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458535/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458535/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458535/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","General Practitioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 7 March 2016 to Question 29559, what average number of patients were registered at each GP surgery in each of the last 15 years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","30294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458536","Department of Health","false","2016-03-14","<p>75% of Senior Civil Servants in the Department are based in London. Some Departmental team responsibilities are strictly policy matters and others may include, or exclusively involve, operational or corporate business activities. The Department does not impose an artificial distinction between ‘policy’ teams and operational or business teams as many teams will be active in both aspects of Government to varying degrees. The titles and topics covered by all the teams making up the Department can be found in the most recent Departmental organograms / structure charts at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://reference.data.gov.uk/gov-structure/organogram/?dept=dh" target="_blank">http://reference.data.gov.uk/gov-structure/organogram/?dept=dh</a></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-03-14T17:33:26.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458536/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458536/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458536/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Department of Health: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of his Department's (a) Senior Civil Servants and (b) core policy civil servants are based in London.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","30312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458537","Department of Health","false","2016-03-14","<p>The Government has committed that by 2020 patients with urgent and emergency care hospital needs will have access to the same high quality hospital care at the weekend as they do during the week. This means that these patients will have access to the same level of consultant review, diagnostic tests and treatments seven days a week. Hospitals will deliver this seven day provision for 25% of the population by March 2017, 50% by March 2018 and the rest of England by 2020.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has also committed that by 2020 everyone will be able to access routine general practitioner appointments at evenings and weekends. NHS 111 will give patients easy, 24/7 access to integrated urgent care services, offering clinical assessment, advice and treatment. A range of professionals will be directly available to speak to callers who need it.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-03-14T11:23:46.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458537/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458537/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458537/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","NHS: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to ensure that seven day NHS provision will be accessible in all parts of the country.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","30318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458538","Department of Health","false","2016-03-16","<p>Improving the capability of the care workforce through continued skills development is a vital investment in the future. This applies to the workforce as a whole but is particularly important for those working in residential homes.</p><p>Ultimately, it is the responsibility of employers to ensure their staff are suitably trained and appropriately supported to undertake the roles for which they are employed.</p><p>The Department is working closely with our delivery partners to support employers in improving the level of skills of the workforce and is spending significant levels of funding to support this work.</p><p>The introduction of the Care Certificate is delivering specific standards for the training of new care workers.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-03-16T12:32:03.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458538/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458538/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458538/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Care Homes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will ensure that (a) training and (b) emotional support is given to carers who work in residential homes.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","30323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458539","Department of Health","false","2016-03-16","<p>The Children and Young People’s Mental Health and Wellbeing Taskforce was established in September 2014 to consider ways to improve how children and young people’s mental health (CYPMH) services are organised, commissioned and provided. Evidence presented to and discussions in the Taskforce underlined the complexity and severity of the current set of challenges facing child and adolescent mental health services, including investment and funding arrangements. The work of the Taskforce resulted in the publication of the Government report, Future in Mind, which established a clear and powerful consensus about system-wide transformation to improve CYPMH.</p><p>This Government is committed to delivering this. An additional £1.4 billion has been made available over the course of this parliament to support this transformation programme, which includes investment in a range of mental health services for children and young people services, including psychiatric services. This includes £150 million to improve eating disorders and £75 million for perinatal mental health services.</p><p>Most of the additional funding is going direct to local areas to invest in transforming their services, but we need to balance this with investment nationally for workforce and system development, which sets the foundations for transformation. As this work progresses at national level, the amount going to local areas to support direct service delivery will gradually increase over the course of the five years.</p><p>Local Transformation Plans developed by clinical commissioning groups, covering all local areas, have been successfully assured by NHS England and funding was released in December 2015 to implement the Plans. These plans must cover the whole spectrum of CYPMH needs.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-03-16T12:28:23.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458539/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458539/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458539/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Mental Health Services: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of the level of investment in psychiatric services for children.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","30335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458540","Department of Health","false","2016-03-16","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p><p>Public Health England, Local Alcohol Profiles for England (LAPE) provides local data alongside national comparisons to support local health improvements. The latest LAPE data can be found at:</p><p><a href="http://fingertips.phe.org.uk/profile/local-alcohol-profiles" target="_blank">http://fingertips.phe.org.uk/profile/local-alcohol-profiles</a></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-03-16T12:40:29.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458540/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458540/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458540/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Alcoholic Drinks: Southampton Itchen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will estimate the proportion of people in Southampton, Itchen constituency who consume more than the recommended daily alcohol intake.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","30328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458541","Department of Health","false","2016-03-16","<p>On 11 February 2016 the Secretary of State made an oral statement, <em>Official Report</em>, <em><a href="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201516/cmhansrd/cm160211/debtext/160211-0002.htm#16021153000002" target="_blank">columns 1763-1765</a></em> in which he announced that he would proceed with the introduction of a new national contract for doctors in training, following advice that there was no realistic prospect of reaching agreement with the British Medical Association.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-03-16T15:33:25.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458541/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458541/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458541/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Junior Doctors: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he has taken to avert further industrial action by junior doctors since the announcement of his intention to impose a new contract.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","30333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458542","Department of Health","false","2016-03-16","<p>In December 2015 the UK National Screening Committee (UK NSC) commissioned an update review into antenatal screening for Group B Streptococcus (GBS) as per its published process. A public consultation is expected to be held in late 2016 for a three-month period; the UK NSC will then review the recommendation for GBS at the successive meeting.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-03-16T15:16:58.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458542/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458542/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458542/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Streptococcus","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the timescale is for the UK National Screening Committee Group B Streptococcus review; when the public consultation on that review will open and close; and when he expects the committee to make a decision on the outcomes of that review.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","30381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458543","Department of Health","false","2016-03-11","<p>The Care Quality Commission (CQC) is the independent regulator of health and adult social care in England. The CQC is responsible for deciding which providers to inspect and when to inspect them. The CQC has provided the following information:</p><p> </p><p>In June 2015, the CQC published the results of three NHS 111 inspection pilots. The NHS 111 services inspected were operated by the Isle of Wight Healthcare Trust, Derbyshire Health United and North West Ambulance Service NHS Trust.</p><p> </p><p>In November 2015, the CQC conducted a comprehensive inspection of Derbyshire Health United. This report has not yet been published. In November 2015, it also conducted a comprehensive inspection of Hertfordshire Urgent Care and published its report on 10 March 2016. The service was rated ‘Good’.</p><p> </p><p>In November 2015, the CQC conducted a focused inspection of South Central Ambulance Trust’s 111 service and published its report in January 2016. In March 2016, the CQC completed a focussed inspection of South West Ambulance Trust’s 111 service and will publish the report in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The remaining providers are scheduled to be inspected in line with the CQC hospital and primary medical services inspection programme during 2016.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-03-11T12:37:55.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458543/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458543/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458543/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","NHS 111","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, on which occasions the Care Quality Commission has inspected each provider of NHS 111 since April 2013.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","30372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458544","Department of Health","false","2016-03-11","<p>The following table shows the number of pre-registration nurses who commenced training each year since 2010. The 2015/16 actual data is not yet available; the figure given is for planned.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Nursing</p></td><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Actual</p></td><td><p>20,092</p></td><td><p>17,741</p></td><td><p>17,219</p></td><td><p>17,568</p></td><td><p>19,147</p></td><td><p>20,033</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><em>Source:</em> multi professional education and training budget monitoring returns</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-03-11T12:45:17.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458544/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458544/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458544/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Nurses: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many nurses commenced training in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","30373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458545","Department of Health","false","2016-03-11","<p>The table provides figures on a United Kingdom basis for the number of trainees entering further training at Foundation Year 1 (F1) for the last 5 years. However, it should be noted that not all doctors commence their training in the UK at F1, and an accurate figure for these is not available.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>7,314</p></td><td><p>7,257</p></td><td><p>7,330</p></td><td><p>7,678</p></td><td><p>7,478</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>The General Medical Council (GMC) issue Certificates of Completion of Training (CCT) to doctors who complete a full GMC approved speciality training programme. The UK figures for the last five years available from the GMC are:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>6,211</p></td><td><p>6,406</p></td><td><p>6,222</p></td><td><p>6,429</p></td><td><p>6,888</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-03-11T13:54:40.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458545/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458545/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458545/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-08","Doctors: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many doctors have (a) commenced and (b) finished their training in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","30386"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458546","Home Office","false","2016-03-11","<p>The Home Office does not collect data on the number of cases of sexual offences flagged as child abuse that have been investigated.</p><p>The Home Office collects information on the number of crimes the police in England and Wales record and the outcomes they assign to these crimes. The Home Office is clear that all crimes reported to the police should be taken seriously, investigated and, where appropriate, taken through the courts and met with tough sentences.</p><p>From the data the Home Office receives, information can only be provided for certain sexual offences that identify that the victim is aged under 18 by the name of the offence in statute, namely:</p><p> Rape of a female child under 16</p><p> Rape of a female child under 13</p><p> Rape of a male child under 16</p><p> Rape of a male child under 13</p><p> Sexual assault on a female child under 13</p><p> Sexual assault on a male child under 13</p><p> Sexual activity involving a child under 13</p><p> Sexual activity involving child under 16</p><p> Sexual grooming (the victim must be under 16)</p><p> Abuse of position of trust in a sexual nature (under 17)</p><p> Abuse of children through sexual exploitation</p><p>Data for these offences by police force area are available in the police recorded crime and outcomes open data available here:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-recorded-crime-open-data-tables</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-03-11T13:57:59.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458546/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458546/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458546/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-08","Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many cases of child abuse flagged by sexual offences have been investigated in each police force area in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","30374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458547","Home Office","false","2016-03-15","<p>The questions have been interpreted as referring to unaccompanied asylum seeking children arriving in the UK.</p><p>Figures on asylum applications for Unaccompanied Asylum Seeking Children (UASC) are published quarterly by the Home Office in the Immigration Statistics release.</p><p>The following table shows applications for asylum from Unaccompanied Asylum Seeking Children, excluding dependants, for nationals of Nigeria, Uganda, Albania and Eritrea during 2015.</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Asylum applications received from Unaccompanied Asylum Seeking Children, excluding dependants, from nationals of Nigeria, Uganda, Albania and Eritrea during 2015</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Nationality</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total applications</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nigeria</p></td><td><p>14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Uganda</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Albania</p></td><td><p>456</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Eritrea</p></td><td><p>694</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Table Notes</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>(1) These data are provisional and subject to change.</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>(2) An Unaccompanied Asylum Seeking Child (UASC) is a person under 18, or who, in the absence of documentary evidence establishing age, appears to be under that age, is applying for asylum on his or her own right and has no relative or guardian in the United Kingdom.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>A copy of the latest release, Immigration Statistics October to December 2015, is available from:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/immigration-statistics-october-to-december-2015</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","30350 ; 30351 ; 30352","2016-03-15T16:47:43.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458547/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458547/answer",,,"