e used.</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="5"><p>(4) London includes both the Metropolitan and City of London Police force areas. No results were returned from City of London Police Force area from 1 January 2012 onwards, as City of London Local Justice area was merged into other reporting areas.</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p>Source: Justice Statistics Analytical Services - Ministry of Justice.</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ref: PQ 30375 &amp; 30376</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","30375","2016-03-11T11:39:46.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458552/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458552/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458552/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-08","Offences against Children: Convictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many cases of child abuse flagged by sexual offences have led to convictions in each police force area in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","30376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458553","Home Office","false","2016-03-15","<p>Serco commissioned an independent investigation by Kate Lampard into the culture and staffing at Yarl's Wood. The report was published in January 2016. Serco has responded quickly to the recommendations in the report and has agreed or completed 32 of the 35 recommendations. These include an increase in staffing levels and introducing changes to policies to ensure that all detainees are treated in a safe and dignified manner. As of 9 March 2016, 55% of Serco’s operational staff at Yarl’s Wood are women.</p><p>The Government is addressing the issue of welfare in detention through its response to Stephen Shaw’s review set out in the Written Ministerial Statement laid before the House on 14 January. This includes a new adults at risk policy and a mental health action plan.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-15T16:43:18.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458553/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458553/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458553/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-08","Yarl's Wood Immigration Removal Centre","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to address the issues raised in the Independent Investigation into conditions at Yarl's Wood in January 2016; and what additional steps she will take to address concerns around (a) staffing arrangements including capacity and training and (b) an inadequate proportion of female officers to care for women at the centre.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","30353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458554","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-14","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-03-14T09:29:33.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458554/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458554/answer","30321 FINAL.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Return to Eastern Europe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458554/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-03-08","Migration: Eastern Europe","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will estimate the number of people from Eastern Europe who have returned to their country of birth from the UK in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","30321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458555","Home Office","false","2016-03-15","<p>The average number of full-time equivalent staff employed by the Disclosure and Barring Service in each year since 2010 is listed in the table below. The DBS was created in 2012 and replaced the Criminal Records Bureau (CRB) and Independent Safeguarding Authority (ISA).</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Average number of Staff</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>667</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>542</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13 (CRB)</p></td><td><p>483</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13 (DBS)</p></td><td><p>730</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>721</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>745</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-03-15T16:40:00.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458555/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458555/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458555/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-08","Disclosure and Barring Service: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many staff have been employed to process Disclosure and Barring Service checks in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","30234"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458556","Home Office","false","2016-03-11","<p>The Home Office does not hold this information centrally.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-03-11T13:50:33.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458556/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458556/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458556/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-08","Human Trafficking: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many warrants for the purposes of establishing whether women are being trafficked have been excluded by her Department in each local authority in Lancashire in each month in 2015.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","30239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458557","Home Office","false","2016-03-15","<p>The accommodation in Kingfisher Unit is used for individuals removed from general association in accordance with Rules 40 (removed from association) and 42 (temporary confinement) of the Detention Centre Rules 2001.</p><p>Rule 40 states that an individual may be removed from association where it appears necessary in the interests of security or safety that they should not associate with other detained persons, either generally or for particular purposes.</p><p>Rule 42 states that a violent or refractory individual may be confined temporarily in special accommodation, but not as a punishment, or after he/she has ceased to be refractory or violent.</p><p>Management information held by the service provider, Serco, for Yarl’s Wood Immigration Removal Centre is only available for the number of instances that the accommodation was used for these purposes and cannot be provided for the numbers of individuals except at disproportionate cost.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-15T16:57:14.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458557/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458557/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458557/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-08","Yarl's Wood Immigration Removal Centre","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many detainees have been held in the Kingfisher Isolation Unit in Yarl's Wood in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","30235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458558","Home Office","false","2016-03-24","<p>Data on cases progressed under the Dublin Convention is recorded on the main immigration database. However, this data is not held in a way that allows it to be reported on automatically and is therefore not currently available.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-24T15:50:36.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458558/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458558/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458558/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458558/answer/previousversion/50864","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-08","Asylum: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many take charge requests under the Dublin III Regulation the UK has accepted from France for unaccompanied children for family reunification in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Yvette Cooper","Normanton, Pontefract and Castleford","Yvette Cooper","30240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458559","Home Office","false","2016-04-04","<p>Data on cases progressed under the Dublin III Regulation is recorded on the main immigration database. However, this data is not held in a way that allows it to be reported on automatically and is therefore not currently available.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-04-04T12:11:34.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458559/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458559/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458559/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458559/answer/previousversion/50865","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-08","Asylum: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many take charge requests under the Dublin III Regulation the UK has accepted from Greece for unaccompanied children for family reunification the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Yvette Cooper","Normanton, Pontefract and Castleford","Yvette Cooper","30241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458560","Home Office","false","2016-03-14","<p>The average length of time taken to consider naturalisation applications in the UK is 135.12 days. In Leeds postal code area the average length of time is 167 days. Both of these figures relate to the period 1 January 2015 to 31 December 2015, which is the most recent period for which statistics on the number of applications considered have been published.</p><p>For straightforward applications where the customer has met all their obligations, the service standard is that 98.5% of cases will be processed within 6 months (183 calendar days).</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-14T15:55:06.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458560/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458560/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458560/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458560/answer/previousversion/50858","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-08","Naturalisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the current average waiting time is for a decision on a naturalisation application in (a) the UK and (b) Leeds.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","30245"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458561","Home Office","false","2016-03-14","<p>Customers are able to book appointments in the following local authority areas:</p><p>Brent, Barnet, Southwark, Gloucestershire, Kent, Lancashire, Hackney, Wandsworth, Enfield, Hertfordshire, Islington, Camden, Bracknell Forest, Leeds, Slough, Merton, Sutton, Poole, Luton, East Riding of Yorkshire, Tower Hamlets, Hammersmith &amp; Fulham, Cambridgeshire, West Sussex, Oldham, Wolverhampton, Trafford, West Berks, Reading, Dudley, Hull, Norfolk, Worcestershire, Redbridge, Westminster, Bolton, Wokingham, Southampton, Warwickshire, Windsor &amp; Maidenhead, York and Pembrokeshire.</p><p>This service will be further rolled out within additional local authority areas over the coming months.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-14T16:19:01.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458561/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458561/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458561/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458561/answer/previousversion/50859","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-08","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, in which local authority areas applications can be made for naturalisation and a British passport at the same time.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","30246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458562","Home Office","false","2016-03-24","<p>Data on cases progressed under the Dublin III Regulation is recorded on the main immigration database. However, this data is not held in a way that allows it to be reported on automatically and is therefore not currently available.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-24T15:50:50.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458562/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458562/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458562/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458562/answer/previousversion/50861","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-08","Asylum: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many take charge requests under the Dublin III Regulation protocols she has agreed to in relation to unaccompanied asylum-seeking children in France with either parents or alleged parents in the UK in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","30244"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458563","Home Office","false","2016-03-14","<p>The Dublin Regulation is an important tool in our ability to manage asylum claims in the EU. The Government recognises that improvements can be made to the operation of the Regulation through simplification, greater flexibility and encouragement of maximum compliance. The underlying principles, however, such as claiming asylum in the first safe country, reuniting families where possible, prevention of secondary movement and assigning responsibility of a claim as soon as possible all remain sound.</p><p>We are cooperating fully with the European Commission’s review of the Dublin Regulation and will continue to make the case these long established principles should continue to be the basis for any future regulation.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-14T15:46:25.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458563/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458563/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458563/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458563/answer/previousversion/50860","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-08","Asylum: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the Dublin III Regulation asylum process; what her proposals are for its reform and improvement; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","30243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458564","Home Office","false","2016-04-04","<p>Data on cases progressed under the Dublin Convention is recorded on the main immigration database. However, this data is not held in a way that allows it to be reported on automatically and is therefore not currently available.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-04-04T12:11:49.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458564/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458564/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458564/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458564/answer/previousversion/50866","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-08","Asylum: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many take charge requests under the Dublin III Regulation the UK has received from other EU member states for family reunification in the (a) unaccompanied minors, (b) family members, (c) dependent persons and (d) discretionary categories in the last 12 months; and how many such requests have been (i) approved, (ii) refused and (iii) remain under consideration.","false","Biography information for Yvette Cooper","Normanton, Pontefract and Castleford","Yvette Cooper","30242"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458565","Home Office","false","2016-03-15","<p>Inspection of vessels by is undertaken by Border Force on a case by case basis depending on the intelligence held and the level of assessed risk.</p><p>Border Force operates an intelligence led and risk assessed approach to managing the maritime border. This allows Border Force to provide effective border controls up and down the country. Border Force maintains close working relationships with law enforcement partners and related agencies who also use an intelligence-led approach in accordance with assessments of known and inferred risk.</p><p>Border Force shares information on possible subjects of interest with EU law enforcement partners and continues to work very closely with them to enable real time interventions where appropriate.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-15T16:52:28.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458565/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458565/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458565/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-08","Sailing Boats","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what arrangements are in place to (a) record and (b) inspect small yachts arriving from Europe at marinas on the UK coastline.","false","Biography information for Dame Angela Watkinson","Hornchurch and Upminster","Dame Angela Watkinson","30153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458566","Home Office","false","2016-03-14","<p>The data requested is not available. The Home Office collects aggregate data against a range of crime types from all police forces but these do not identify the gender of the victim.</p><p>We are developing the Home Office Data Hub to gather more detailed crime level data from forces, including the potential to collect the gender of victims and present statistics on it in the future. Forces are gradually migrating to supplying their main crime data to the new system.</p><p>The recent Office for National Statistics publication &quot;Focus on Violence and Sexual Offences&quot;:</p><p>https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice/compendium/focusonviolentcrimeandsexualoffences/yearendingmarch2015</p><p>highlights partial and experimental statistics on proportions of victims by gender based on a subset of forces.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-03-14T15:39:33.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458566/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458566/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458566/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458566/answer/previousversion/50867","Biography information for Karen Bradley","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-08","Crimes of Violence: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many instances of violence against women were recorded in (a) Cardiff and (b) Vale of Glamorgan in each of the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","30172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458567","Home Office","false","2016-03-14","<p>The Home Office does not hold this information in the format requested. To obtain it would incur a disproportionate cost.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-14T15:50:18.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458567/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458567/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458567/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458567/answer/previousversion/50863","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-08","Refugees: Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many refugees have (a) applied for and (b) been successful in obtaining a visa to enter the UK from the Republic of Ireland in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","30176"
