"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458591","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-15","<p>The Department for Transport and Network Rail have undertaken early discussions with key stakeholders in the rail freight industry, including a meeting with the Rail Freight Group, regarding options for the sale of rail freight sites owned by Network Rail.</p><p> </p><p>The on-going process of identifying options for the sale of rail freight sites is at a very early stage. Key stakeholders will be engaged throughout the process.</p><p> </p><p>Network Rail is required to consult should it wish to dispose of land in which it has an interest and which may be important to the continuing operation and future development of the network. A full consultation process will be undertaken before any final decision is taken about the sale of freight sites owned by Network Rail.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-15T16:52:49.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458591/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458591/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458591/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-08","Railways: Freight","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what consultation he plans to undertake before any rail freight sites owned by Network Rail are sold.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","30282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458592","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-11","<p>This was a commercial matter for Network Rail. The total cost to Network Rail of acquiring the lease interests of the Freight Operators under Project Mountfield was £220 million.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-11T12:32:41.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458592/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458592/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458592/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-08","Railways: Freight","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much Network Rail paid to buy back land from rail freight owners in October 2014.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","30287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458593","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-11","<p>This decision was made by Network Rail, and I have sought clarification from the company as to the reasons. I am informed that the purchase was made to increase competition and efficiency across the freight industry, opening up the market to operators.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-11T12:35:51.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458593/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458593/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458593/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-08","Railways: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, for what reasons Network Rail bought back rail lands in October 2014; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","30288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458594","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-11","<p>British Rail did not sell land directly to private freight companies but transferred land to the different freight entities within its own operations in advance of the sale of the freight business. It would no longer be possible at this point to extrapolate the land value from the company value.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-11T12:39:08.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458594/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458594/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458594/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-08","Railways: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much money accrued to the public purse at the time of rail privatisation from land sold by British Rail to private freight companies.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","30289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458595","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-11","<p>No decision has been taken about which sites owned by Network Rail should be sold. Network Rail is reviewing the complete freight land holdings and the options for the portfolio for the future to identify those sites which are surplus. This will include an assessment of which sites are required, or are likely to be required in the future, for freight use.</p><p> </p><p>A robust process of identifying options for the sale of rail freight sites is on-going but at a very early stage, and a full consultation process will be undertaken before any final decision is taken about the sale of freight sites owned by Network Rail.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-11T12:43:36.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458595/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458595/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458595/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-08","Railways: Freight","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what land Network Rail is considering selling which can be utilised for rail freight .","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","30290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458596","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-16","<p>The department assumed that the Bus Service Operators Grant (BSOG) was passed on to passengers 50% through lower fares and 50% through increased service levels as a working assumption made in the absence of better relevant evidence. The estimate of the effect of keeping fares lower as a result of BSOG was derived by using the National Bus Model, which combined assumptions based on the evidence available with actual data on passenger numbers, fares and service levels.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-16T10:33:29.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458596/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458596/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458596/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-08","Bus Service Operators Grant","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 3 March 2016 to Question 28183, using what evidence base his departmental economists (a) normally assume operators pass subsidy received on to passengers at a rate of 50 per cent through lower fares and at a rate of 50 per cent through increased service levels and (b) estimate that the Bus Service Operators' Grant has the effect of keeping fares 3 per cent lower in England outside London.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","30285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458597","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-16","<p>The income available to the Greater London Authority through the Business Rates Retention Scheme was £863.2 million in 2013/2014 and £936.2 million in 2014/2015. The income is forecast to be £1.0396 billion in 2015/2016.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-16T15:44:32.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458597/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458597/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458597/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-08","Bus Service Operators Grant","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 3 March 2016 to Question 28284, how much the Business Rate Retention Scheme has raised for the Greater London Authority in each year since the scheme's introduction.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","30286"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458598","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-15","<p>The capacity of a freight site is determined by a number of factors including the parameters of the site, the loading capabilities within the site and the capacity of the rail network connecting to the site. The department has not made any assessment of the capacity in freight sites owned by Network Rail. Network Rail does not hold all the information required to make such an assessment as this is partly held by those freight operators who manage the sites.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-15T16:55:46.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458598/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458598/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458598/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-08","Railways: Freight","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of freight capacity in freight sites owned by Network Rail.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","30283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458599","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-11","<p>My Department has not made an assessment of the effect of this decision. It is for Network Rail to ensure the right approach to its insurance cover to provide value for money, in line with Managing Public Money guidance.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-11T12:49:43.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458599/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458599/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458599/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-08","Network Rail: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to page 67 of Network Rail Infrastructure Ltd's Regulatory Financial Statements for the year ended 31 March 2015, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of Network Rail's reduction in insurance cover on that company's finances.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","30249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458600","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-11","<p>This transaction relates to funding commitments announced by the Government in Autumn 2014. These decisions were taken in order to make the most effective use of the department's resources in financial year 2014/15 and progress delivery for passengers.</p><p> </p><p>In accordance with Clause 2.4 of the Facility Agreement, the department provided Network Rail with a £155 million grant in exchange for a £125 million reduction in the Available Commitment of the Facility and £30.5 million worth of work to be brought forward into Control Period 5 - the time period covered by the Facility Agreement.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-11T12:14:54.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458600/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458600/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458600/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-08","Network Rail: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to page 35 of Network Rail Infrastructure Ltd's Regulatory Financial Statements for the year ended 31 March 2015, what cash funding his Department has committed to the (a) Reading Station redevelopment and (b) Great Western Electrification Programme in order to reduce the amount being added to Network Rail's Regulatory Asset Base; and for what reasons that policy has been adopted.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","30250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458601","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-16","<p>I and my officials have met and corresponded with industry representatives to discuss the issue of disruptive passengers on a number of occasions over the last year. In particular we have been working closely with airlines, airports, the police and duty free retailers to understand the challenges posed by disruptive behaviour on aircraft and to explore practical steps that can be taken to both reduce the frequency of these instances and to ensure that they are dealt with appropriately when they do occur. We are very supportive of industry’s efforts, including to collating and disseminating best practice and guidance; we will continue to provide assistance where appropriate.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","30226 ; 30227 ; 30230","2016-03-16T09:59:46.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458601/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458601/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458601/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-08","Aviation: Alcoholic Drinks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what guidance his Department issues to airlines on passenger alcohol consumption.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","30231"
